cessdate=February 6, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000202194940/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms14.htm |archivedate=February 2, 2000 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 1991\n| [[Environmental Media Awards]]\n| Children\u2019s Television Program \u2013 Animated\n| episode ''Whales Tales''\n| {{won}}\n| <ref name=\"EMA\">{{cite web |title=EMA Awards - Past Recipients and Honorees |publisher=[[Environmental Media Association]] |url=https://www.green4ema.org/ema-awards/ema-awards-past-recipients-and-honorees |accessdate=April 11, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"emmy91\"/>\n{{end}}\n\nIn January 2009, IGN named ''Tiny Toons'' as the 41st in their Top 100 Animated TV Shows list.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tv.ign.com/top-100-animated-tv-series/41.html |title=Video Games, Wikis, Cheats, Walkthroughs, Reviews, News & Videos - IGN |website=Tv.ign.com |accessdate=September 10, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211081204/http://tv.ign.com/top-100-animated-tv-series/41.html |archivedate=November 2, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Merchandise==\n===Print===\n''Tiny Toon Adventures Magazine'', a quarterly children's magazine based on the series, debuted in October 1990. Issues #1\u20134 were published by [[DC Comics]], and issues #5\u20137 were released by Welsh Publishing Group. The final issue was cover-dated Spring 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comics.org/issue/832609/ |title=GCD - Issue - Tiny Toon Adventures Magazine #7 |website=[[Grand Comics Database]] |accessdate=April 11, 2020 }}</ref> Also, various storybooks were published by the [[Little Golden Books|Little Golden Book]] company, including a few episode adaptations and some original stories (''Lost in the Fun House'' and ''Happy Birthday, Babs!''). ''Tiny Toon Adventures'' also had a comic book series made by [[Warner Bros.]] and DC. The characters also made occasional cameo appearances in the ''[[Animaniacs]]'', ''[[Freakazoid!]]'' and ''[[Pinky and the Brain]]'' comic books.{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n\n===Toys and video games===\n{{Main|List of Tiny Toon Adventures video games}}\nSince its debut, numerous [[video game]]s based on ''Tiny Toons'' have been released. There have been no less than nine titles based on the series released after its original television run and as recently as 2002. Many companies have held the development and publishing rights for the games, including [[Konami]] (during the 1990s), [[Atari]], [[NewKidCo]], [[Conspiracy Games]], [[Warthog Games Limited|Warthog]], [[Terraglyph Interactive Studios]], and [[Treasure Co. Ltd|Treasure]]. Toys for the series included plush dolls and plastic figures, primarily made by [[Playskool]].\n\n===Home media===\n''[[Tiny Toon Adventures: How I Spent My Vacation]]'' was released on [[DVD]] on August 21, 2012. There are currently no plans to release the two specials (''Spring Break'' and ''Night Ghoulery'') on [[DVD]].  In the early to mid-1990s, Warner Bros. had released several videos, including ''Tiny Toon Adventures: How I Spent My Vacation'' (a direct-to-video release which later aired as a four-part TV episode), ''Best of Buster and Babs'', ''Two-Tone Town'', ''Tiny Toons: Big Adventures'', ''Tiny Toons: Island Adventures'', ''Tiny Toons: Music Television'', ''Tiny Toons: Fiendishly Funny Adventures'', ''Tiny Toons: Night Ghoulery'' and ''It's a Wonderful Tiny Toons Christmas Special''.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! DVD name\n! Ep #\n! Release date\n! Special Features\n! Notes\n|-\n| Season 1 Volume 1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 35\n| {{Start date|2008|7|29}}\n| From Looney Tunes to Tiny Toons: A Wacky Evolution, featurette\n| Was released concurrently with the first season of ''[[Freakazoid!]]''. \"The Looney Beginning\" episode is uncut on the set.\n|-\n| Season 1 Volume 2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 30\n| {{Start date|2009|4|21}}\n| None, aside from trailers\n| Was released concurrently with the second season of ''[[Freakazoid!]]''. Two episodes are edited: \"Tiny Toons Music Television\" (a phone number gag was removed) and \"Son of the Wacko World of Sports\" (wraparounds and title cards were removed).{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n|-\n| Volume 3: Crazy Crew Rescues\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17\n| {{Start date|2013|1|8}}\n| None, aside from trailers\n| The previously-banned episode \"Elephant Issues\" is included in this set. Initially when the set was announced, the content list did not contain the episode due to its controversial \"One Beer\" segment.<ref name=\"tvshowsondvd.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Tiny-Toon-Adventures-missing-episode-included/17575 |title=Tiny Toon Adventures DVD news: Missing episode, 'Elephant Issues,' to be included! |website=TVShowsOnDVD.com |date=2013-01-08 |accessdate=2016-09-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503155638/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Tiny-Toon-Adventures-missing-episode-included/17575 |archivedate=2016-05-03 }}</ref>\n|-\n| Volume 4: Looney Links\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16\n| {{Start date|2013|5|28}}\n| None, aside from trailers\n| The original release contained a glitch which Warner Bros. fixed by the end of July. Also, \"Best of Buster Bunny Day\" is missing its second wraparound scene.{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n|}\n\n==History==\n===Preproduction===\nAccording to writer [[Paul Dini]], ''Tiny Toons'' originated as an idea by [[Terry Semel]], the then-president of [[Warner Bros.]], who wanted to \"inject new life into the [[Warner Bros. Animation]] department,\" and at the same time create a series with junior versions of [[List of Looney Tunes and Merrie Melodies characters|Looney Tunes characters]]. Semel proposed that the new series would be a show based on ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' where the characters were either young versions of the original ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' and ''[[Merrie Melodies]]'' characters or new characters as the offspring of the original characters.<ref name=\"creation\">{{cite magazine |last=Miller |first=Bob |title=NEW TOONS ON THE BLOCK: They're attending Acme Looniversity & hoping to graduate as classic cartoon characters |magazine=[[Comic Scene]] |publisher=[[Starlog|Starlog Group]] |issue=15 |pages=33\u201339, 68 |date=1990}}</ref> The idea of a series with the basis of younger and junior versions of cartoon characters was common at the time; the era in which ''Tiny Toons'' was produced for had such cartoons as ''[[Muppet Babies (1984 TV series)|Muppet Babies]]'', ''[[A Pup Named Scooby-Doo]]'', ''[[Tom & Jerry Kids]]'' and ''[[The Flintstones Kids]]''. [[Warner Bros.]] chose to do the same because Spielberg wanted to make a series similar to ''[[Looney Tunes]]'', as series producer/show-runner Tom Ruegger explained: \"Well, I think in [[Warner Bros.]] case, they had the opportunity to work with Steven Spielberg] on a project [...] But he didn't want to just work on characters that [[Chuck Jones]], [[Friz Freleng]], [[Robert McKimson|Bob McKimson]] and [[Bob Clampett]] made famous and created. He wanted to be involved with the creation of some ''new'' characters.\" The result was a series similar to ''Looney Tunes'' without the use of the same characters.<ref name=\"creation\"/>\n\nOn January 20, 1987,<ref name=\"collab2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318258,00.html |title=SUFFERIN' SUCCOTASH! IT'S LOONEY TUNES, TAKE TWO |date=September 28, 1990 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> the Warner Bros. Animation studio approached [[Steven Spielberg]] to collaborate with Semel and [[Warner Bros.]] head of licensing Dan Romanelli on Semel's ideas.<ref name=\"creation\"/> They eventually decided that the new characters would be similar to the ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' characters with no direct relation. However, ''Tiny Toons'' did not go into production then, nor was it even planned to be made for television; the series initially was to be a [[theatrical]] [[feature-length film]].<ref name=\"collab\"/><ref name=\"creation\"/>\n\nOn December 27, 1988, ''Tiny Toons'' was changed from a film to a television series, with [[Jean MacCurdy]] overseeing production of the first 65 episodes.<ref name=\"creation\"/> MacCurdy said that ''Tiny Toons'' was changed to a television series to \"reach a broader audience\".<ref name=\"collab\"/> For the series, MacCurdy hired [[Tom Ruegger]], who previously wrote cartoons for [[Filmation]] and [[Hanna-Barbera]], to be a producer.<ref name=\"creation\"/> In January 1989, Ruegger and writer [[Wayne Kaatz]] began developing the characters and the setting of \"Acme Acres\" with Spielberg.<ref name=\"creation\"/>\n\nOn January 9, 1989, [[Warner Bros. Animation]] chose its voice actors from over 1,200 auditions and put together its 100-person production staff.<ref name=\"collab\"/> On April 13, 1989, full production of series episodes began with five overseas animation houses and a total budget of $25 million.<ref name=\"collab\"/> The first 65 episodes of the series aired in syndication on 135 stations, beginning in September 1990.<ref name=\"Lenburg1999\" /> During that time, ''Tiny Toons'' was a huge success and got higher ratings than its ''[[The Disney Afternoon|Disney Afternoon]]'' competitors in some affiliates. After a successful run in syndication, Fox attained the rights for season 3. Production of the series halted in late 1992 to make way for ''[[Animaniacs]]'' to air the following year.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Portal|Animation|Cartoon|1990s}}\n* {{IMDb title|0098929|Tiny Toon Adventures}}\n* {{bcdb |Warner_Bros_/Television/Tiny_Toon_Adventures/ |Tiny Toon Adventures }}\n* {{tv.com show|tiny-toon-adventures|Tiny Toon Adventures}}\n* {{URL |http://toonopedia.com/tinytoon.htm |''Tiny Toon Adventures''}} at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]\n\n{{Tiny Toon Adventures}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Children's Animated Program}}\n{{Looney Tunes & Merrie Melodies}}\n{{Warner Bros. animation and comics}}\n{{Fox Kids}}\n{{Kids' WB}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1990s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American daily animated television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American satirical television series]]\n[[Category:1990 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1992 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program winners]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:First-run syndicated television programs in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fox Kids original programming]]\n[[Category:Kids' WB original programs]]\n[[Category:Looney Tunes]]\n[[Category:Looney Tunes television series]]\n[[Category:Self-reflexive television]]\n[[Category:1990s American surreal comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Amblin Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Television series by Warner Bros. Animation]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Tom Ruegger]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Tiny Toon Adventures| ]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about rabbits and hares]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the series|the video game of the same name|Tiny Toon Adventures (video game)}}\n{{short description|Animated television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Tiny Toon Adventures\n| image                = Tinytoons.jpg\n| caption              = Title card\n| show_name_2          = 'Steven Spielberg Presents: Tiny Toon Adventures'\n| genre                = [[Comedy]]<br> [[Slapstick]]<br> [[Satire]]\n| runtime              = 22 minutes approx.\n| creator              = [[Tom Ruegger]]\n| theme_music_composer = [[Bruce Broughton]]\n| composer             = {{plainlist|\n* [[Bruce Broughton]]\n* [[Steven Bernstein (musician)|Steven Bernstein]]\n* [[Steven Bramson]]\n* [[Don Davis (composer)|Don Davis]]\n* Carl Johnson\n* Albert Lloyd Olson\n* [[William Ross (composer)|William Ross]]\n* [[Arthur B. Rubinstein]]\n* [[Fred Steiner]]\n* [[Morton Stevens]]|\n* [[Richard Stone (composer)|Richard Stone]]\n* [[Stephen James Taylor]]\n* [[Mark Watters]]\n* [[John Debney]]\n}}\n| voices               = {{plainlist|\n* [[Charlie Adler]]\n* [[Tress MacNeille]]\n* [[Joe Alaskey]]\n* [[Don Messick]]\n* [[Kath Soucie]]\n* [[Maurice LaMarche]]\n* [[Frank Welker]]\n* [[Rob Paulsen]]\n* [[Danny Cooksey]]\n* [[Cree Summer]]\n* [[Jeff Bergman]]\n* [[Candi Milo]]\n* [[Noel Blanc]]\n* [[June Foray]]\n* [[Jim Cummings]]\n* [[John Kassir]] (season 3)\n* [[Stan Freberg]]\n* [[Bob Bergen]]\n* [[Greg Burson]]\n}}\n| picture_format       = [[NTSC]]\n| audio_format         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Monaural|Mono]]\n* [[Dolby Stereo]]\n* [[Dolby Surround]]\n}}\n| producer             = {{plainlist|\n* [[Tom Ruegger]]\n* [[Sherri Stoner]]\n}}\n| executive_producer   = [[Steven Spielberg]]\n| company              = {{plainlist|\n* [[Warner Bros. Animation]]\n* [[Amblin Entertainment]]\n}}\n| distributor          = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| network              = {{plainlist|\n* [[CBS]] (pilot only)\n* [[Broadcast syndication|Syndicated]] (1990\u201392)\n* [[Fox Kids]] (1992\u20131995\n}}\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|1990|9|14}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|1992|12|6}}\n| num_seasons          = 3\n| list_episodes        = List of Tiny Toon Adventures episodes\n| num_episodes         = 98 (163 segments) \n| related              = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[The Plucky Duck Show]]''\n* ''[[Animaniacs]]''\n* ''[[Freakazoid!]]''\n* ''[[Pinky and the Brain]]''\n* ''[[Pinky, Elmyra & the Brain]]''\n}}\n|}}\n\n'''''Tiny Toon Adventures''''' is an American animated comedy television series that was broadcast from September 14, 1990 to December 6, 1992 as the first collaborative effort of [[Warner Bros. Animation]] and [[Steven Spielberg]]'s [[Amblin Entertainment]] after being conceived in the late 1980s by [[Tom Ruegger]].<ref name=factory>{{cite news|last=Trusdell|first=Brian|title=Focus : Warner's Toon Factory for the 1990s|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-05-28/news/tv-6798_1_tiny-toons/|accessdate=10 May 2011|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 28, 1995|location=USA}}</ref>  The show follows the adventures of a group of young cartoon characters who attend [[Acme Looniversity]] to become the next generation of characters from the ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' series.\n\nThe pilot episode, \"The Looney Beginning\", aired as a prime-time special on [[CBS]] on September 14, 1990,<ref name=tvtango>{{cite web|title=TV Listings for - September 14, 1990 - TV Tango|url=http://www.tvtango.com/listings/1990/09/14|publisher=TV Tango|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> while the series itself was featured in first-run syndication for the first two seasons. The final season was aired on [[Fox Kids]]. The series ended production in 1992 in favor of ''[[Animaniacs]]''; however, two specials were produced in 1994.<ref name=springbreak>{{cite news|last=Mendoza|first=N.F.|title=SHOWS FOR YOUNGSTERS AND THEIR PARENTS TOO : Spielberg's 'Tiny Toons' break for prime time and the rites of spring|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-03-27/news/tv-38816_1_tiny-toons-spring-break/|accessdate=10 May 2011|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 27, 1994|location=USA}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\n===Premise===\n''Tiny Toon Adventures'' is a cartoon set in the fictional town of '''Acme Acres''', where most of the ''Tiny Toons'' and ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' characters live. The characters attend '''Acme Looniversity''', a school whose faculty primarily consists of the mainstays of the classic [[Warner Bros.]] cartoons, such as [[Bugs Bunny]], [[Daffy Duck]], [[Porky Pig]], [[Sylvester the Cat]], [[Wile E. Coyote]] and [[Elmer Fudd]]. In the series, the university is founded to teach cartoon characters how to become funny. The school is not featured in every episode, as not all of its storylines revolve around the school.\n\nLike the [[Looney Tunes]], the series makes use of [[cartoon physics|cartoon violence]] (e.g. [[Anvil#Television and film|anvils]] falling on someone, liberal use of explosives) and [[slapstick]]. The series parodies and references the current events of the early 1990s and [[Hollywood]] culture. Occasionally, episodes delve into veiled ethical and morality stories of [[ecology]], [[self-esteem]], and [[crime]].\n\n===Characters===\n{{Main|List of Tiny Toon Adventures characters}}\n[[Image:Promo tiny toon .jpg|left|thumb|210px|Artwork displaying a majority of the [[List of characters in Tiny Toon Adventures|''Tiny Toon'' cast]].]]\n<!--please don't re-add the list to this section; see talk page-->\nThe series centers on a group of young cartoon characters who attend a school called [[Acme Corporation|Acme]] [[Acme Looniversity|Looniversity]] to be the next generation of ''Looney Tunes'' characters. Most of the Tiny Toons characters were designed to resemble younger versions of Warner Bros.' most popular Looney Tunes animal characters by exhibiting similar traits and looks. The two main characters are both rabbits: [[Buster Bunny]], a blue male rabbit, and [[Babs Bunny]], a pink female rabbit not related to Buster, Plucky Duck, a green male duck, Hamton J. Pig, a pink male pig. Other major characters in the cast are generally nonhuman as well. These include [[Fifi La Fume]], a purple-and-white female skunk; [[Shirley The Loon]], a white female [[loon]]; [[Dizzy Devil]], a purple tasmanian devil; [[Furrball]], a blue cat; [[Sweetie Pie (Tiny Toon Adventures)|Sweetie Pie]], a pink canary; [[Calamity Coyote]], a bluish-gray coyote; [[Little Beeper]], a red-orange roadrunner; and [[Gogo Dodo]], a zany green dodo. Two human characters, [[Montana Max]] and [[Elmyra Duff]], are regarded as the main villains of the series and also are students of Acme Looniversity. As villains, Elmyra is seen as an extreme pet lover while Montana Max is a spoiled rich brat who either owns lots of toys or polluting factories. Supporting characters included [[Li'l Sneezer]], a gray mouse with powerful sneezes; [[Concord Condor]], a purple condor; [[Byron Basset]], a usually sleeping basset hound; [[Bookworm (Tiny Toon Adventures)|Bookworm]], a green worm with glasses; [[Arnold the Pit Bull]], a muscular white pit bull; [[Fowlmouth]], a white rooster with horrid language; [[Barky Marky]], a brown dog, and [[Mary Melody]], a young African American human girl.\n\nFeeding off the characters are the more traditional Looney Tunes such as Bugs Bunny, Daffy Duck, and Porky Pig among others. Most of the adults teach classes at Acme Looniversity and serve as mentors to the Tiny Toons while others fill secondary positions as needed.\n\n==Production==\n\n===Writers===\nThe series and the show's characters were developed by series producer, head writer and cartoonist [[Tom Ruegger]], division leader [[Jean MacCurdy]], associate producer and artist Alfred Gimeno and story editor/writer [[Wayne Kaatz]]. Among the first writers on the series were [[Jim Reardon]], [[Tom Minton]], and Eddie Fitzgerald. The character and scenery designers included Alfred Gimeno, Ken Boyer, [[Dan Haskett]], Karen Haskett, and many other artists and directors. The series was actually planned to be a feature film. Once Steven Spielberg was attached, numerous things changed, including the idea of turning the movie into a television series.\n\n\"Buster and Babs Go To Hawaii\" was co-written by three then-teenage girls who were fans of the show.<ref name=writers>{{cite news|last=Berkman|first=Meredith|title=Adventures among the 'Toons'|url=http://ew.com/ew/article/0,,313220,00.html|accessdate=28 May 2011|newspaper=[[Entertainment Weekly]] issue #51|date=February 1, 1991|location=USA}}</ref>\n\n===Casting info===\nVoice director [[Andrea Romano (voice director)|Andrea Romano]] auditioned over 1,200 voices for the series and chose more than a dozen main voice actors.<ref name=\"collab\">{{cite web|title=Tiny Toon Adventures - Long-Awaited 'Volume 3' DVD Brings Toons from 2nd, 3rd Season|url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Tiny-Toon-Adventures-Volume-3/17543|publisher=TV Shows on DVD|last=Lambert|first=David|date=September 9, 2012|accessdate=September 28, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929234612/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Tiny-Toon-Adventures-Volume-3/17543|archivedate=September 29, 2012}}</ref> The role of Buster Bunny was given to [[Charlie Adler]], who gave the role, as producer [[Tom Ruegger]] said, \"a great deal of energy\".<ref name=\"creation\"/> The role of Babs Bunny was given to [[Tress MacNeille]]. Writer [[Paul Dini]] said that MacNeille was good for the role because she could do both Babs' voice and the voices of her impressions.<ref name=\"creation\"/> Voice actors [[Joe Alaskey]] and [[Don Messick]] were given the roles of Plucky Duck and Hamton J. Pig, respectively. [[Danny Cooksey]] played Montana Max and, according to [[Paul Dini]], was good for the role because he could do a \"tremendous mean voice.\" Cooksey was also the only voice actor in the cast who was not an adult.<ref name=\"creation\"/> [[Cree Summer]] played the roles of Elmyra Duff and Mary Melody; former ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' cast member [[Gail Matthius]] played Shirley the Loon, and [[Kath Soucie]] had the roles of Fifi La Fume and Li'l Sneezer. Other actors for the series included [[Maurice LaMarche]] as the voice of Dizzy Devil; [[Candi Milo]] as the voice of Sweetie, [[Frank Welker]] as the voice of Gogo Dodo, Furrball, Byron Basset, Calamity Coyote, Little Beeper, Barky Marky, and other voices; and [[Rob Paulsen]] as the voice of Fowlmouth, Arnold the Pit Bull, Concord Condor, and other characters. The legendary voice behind the Looney Tunes, [[Mel Blanc]], was set to reprise his roles as the classic characters, but died in July 1989. His characters were recast by the likes of [[Jeff Bergman]], [[Joe Alaskey]], [[Greg Burson]], and Mel's son, [[Noel Blanc]].\n\nDuring production of the series' third season, Charlie Adler left the show due to a conflict with the producers. Adler was upset that he had not landed a role in ''[[Animaniacs]]'' while voice actors with smaller roles in ''Tiny Toon Adventures'' like [[Rob Paulsen]], [[Maurice LaMarche]], and [[Frank Welker]] were given starring roles in the new series.<ref name=\"kennedy\"/> [[John Kassir]] replaced Adler for the remainder of the show's run (although Adler would eventually return to voice Buster in the cancelled video game, ''[[Tiny Toon Adventures: Defenders of the Universe]]''). Joe Alaskey, the voice of Plucky Duck, also left ''Tiny Toons'' for financial reasons, but returned when an agreement was reached with the studio.<ref name=\"kennedy\"/>\n\n===Animation===\nIn order to complete 65 episodes for the first season, [[Warner Bros. Animation]] and [[Amblin Entertainment]] contracted several different [[North American]] and international animation houses. These animation studios included Tokyo Movie Shinsha (now known as [[TMS Entertainment]]), [[Wang Film Productions]], [[AKOM]], [[Freelance Animators New Zealand]], Encore Cartoons, [[StarToons]],<ref name=startoons>{{cite news|last=Owens|first=John|title=Drawing On Experience|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-07-05/features/9203010023_1_animation-studios-hanna-barbera-studios-hollywood-cartoon|accessdate=1 October 2011|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=July 5, 1992}}</ref> and [[Kennedy Cartoons]].<ref>Credits from various ''Tiny Toon Adventures'' episodes.{{Clarify|date=January 2009}}</ref> Tokyo Movie Shinsha also animated the series' opening sequence. Some of the Warner Bros. staff disliked working with Kennedy Cartoons due to the animation studio's inconsistent quality, and episodes that they animated were often subject to multiple re-takes. In other cases, such as the debut episode \"The Looney Beginning\", portions of Kennedy Cartoons-animated episodes were re-animated by another animation studio.<ref name=\"kennedy\">{{cite web|url=http://platypuscomix.net/people/ruegger2.html|title=Platypus Comix interviews......Tom Ruegger! (part II)|last=Paltridge|first=Peter|date=July 2006|work=Platypus Comix|accessdate=2006-08-23}}{{Unreliable source?|date=January 2009}}</ref> Kennedy Cartoons was actually dropped after the end of the series' first season.\n\n''Tiny Toon Adventures'' was made with a higher production value than standard television animation. It had a [[cel]] count that was more than double that of most animated television shows then.<ref name=\"creation\"/> The series had about 25,000 cels per episode instead of the standard 10,000, making it unique in that characters moved more fluidly.<ref name=\"creation\"/> [[Pierre DeCelles]], an animation producer, described storyboarding for the series as \"fun but a big challenge because I always had a short schedule, and it's not always easy to work full blast nonstop\".\n\n===Music===\nDuring the development of the show [[Steven Spielberg]] said that [[Warner Bros.]] would use a full orchestra, which some thought too expensive and impossible, but they ended up agreeing. [[Warner Bros.]] selected [[Bruce Broughton]] to write the theme tune (for which he would win a [[Daytime Emmy]] along with [[Tom Ruegger]] and [[Wayne Kaatz]], who both worked with Broughton on the lyrics) and serve as [[music supervisor]]. Screen credits for the composers were given based on the amount of music composed for, or composed and reused in, the episode.\n\nTwenty-six other composers were contracted to create original dramatic underscore for each different episode during the series run: Julie and [[Steven Bernstein (musician)|Steve Bernstein]], [[Steven Bramson]], [[Don Davis (composer)|Don Davis]], [[John Debney]], Ron Grant, [[Les Hooper]], Carl Johnson, Elliot Kaplan, Arthur Kempel, Ralph Kessler, Albert Lloyd Olson, [[Hummie Mann]], [[Dennis McCarthy (composer)|Dennis McCarthy]], [[Joel McNeely]], Peter Myers, [[Laurence Rosenthal]], [[William Ross (composer)|William Ross]], [[Arthur B. Rubinstein]], J. Eric Schmidt, David Slonaker, [[Fred Steiner]], [[Morton Stevens]], [[Richard Stone (composer)|Richard Stone]], [[Stephen James Taylor]] and [[Mark Watters]]. The composers conducted their own music. Of these composers, Broughton, Bramson, Davis, Olson, Stone, Taylor and Watters wrote the score to ''[[Tiny Toon Adventures: How I Spent My Vacation]]''.\n\nThese composers would later write the musical scores for shows including ''[[Animaniacs]]'' and ''[[The Sylvester & Tweety Mysteries]].''\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Tiny Toon Adventures episodes}}\n{{:List of Tiny Toon Adventures episodes}}\n\n==Voice cast==\n* [[Charlie Adler]] \u2013 Buster Bunny (1990-1992)\n** [[John Kassir]] \u2013 Buster Bunny (1992-1995)\n* [[Joe Alaskey]] \u2013 Plucky Duck\n* [[Danny Cooksey]] \u2013 Montana Max\n* [[Maurice LaMarche]] \u2013 Dizzy Devil \n* [[Tress MacNeille]] \u2013 Babs Bunny\n* [[Gail Matthius]] \u2013 Shirley the Loon\n* [[Don Messick]] \u2013 Hamton J. Pig\n* [[Candi Milo]] \u2013 Sweetie\n* [[Rob Paulsen]] \u2013 Arnold the Pitbull, Fowlmouth\n* [[Kath Soucie]] \u2013 Fifi La Fume, Sneezer\n* [[Cree Summer]] \u2013 Elmyra Duff, Mary Melody\n* [[Frank Welker]] \u2013 Gogo Dodo, Furrball, Byron Basset, Calamity Coyote, Little Beeper\n\n===Recurring cast===\n* [[Jeff Altman]] \u2013 Dr. Gene Splicer\n* [[Orson Bean]] \u2013 [[Mister Geppetto|Geppetto]]\n* [[Michael Bell (actor)|Michael Bell]] \u2013 [[Batman]] (in \"Hollywood Plucky\")\n* [[Jeff Bennett]] \u2013 [[Batman]] (in \"The Return of Batduck\"), [[Kevin Costner]]\n* [[Bob Bergen]] \u2013 [[Porky Pig]] (in \"[[Animaniacs]]\" and \"Hero Hamton\"), [[Tweety]] (in \"[[Animaniacs]]\")\n* [[Jeff Bergman]] \u2013 [[Bugs Bunny]], [[Daffy Duck]], [[Foghorn Leghorn]], Dr. I.Q. Hi, [[Darth Vader|Duck Vader]], [[Elmer Fudd]] (in \"Her Wacky Highness,\" \"Psychic Fun-omenon Day,\" \"Tiny Toon Music Television,\" \"K-ACME TV,\" and \"Viewer Mail Day\"), [[Sylvester the Cat|Sylvester]] (in \"Animaniacs,\" \"Viewer Mail Day,\" and \"The Son of the Wacko World of Sports\"), [[Tweety]], [[Yosemite Sam]] (in \"The Wide World of Elmyra,\" \"Looniversity Daze,\" \"Son of Looniversity Daze,\" and \"K-ACME TV\"), [[Tasmanian Devil (Looney Tunes)|Tasmanian Devil]] (in \"Prom-ise Her Anything\" and \"[[Animaniacs]]\")\n* [[Stephen Bishop (actor)|Stephen Bishop]] \u2013 Mailman\n* [[Noel Blanc]] \u2013 [[Porky Pig]] (in \"The Wacko World of Sports,\" \"Fields of Honey,\" and \"The Acme Bowl\"), [[Tasmanian Devil (Looney Tunes)|Tasmanian Devil]] (in \"You Asked For It Part 1\"), The Great and Powerful Principal, Additional Voices\n* [[Susan Blu]] \u2013 Sphinxy\n* [[Valri Bromfield]] \u2013 Fran, [[Mary Hart]]less\n* [[Julie Brown]] \u2013 Julie Bruin\n* [[Rodger Bumpass]] \u2013 [[Donald Trump|Ronald Grump]]\n* [[Greg Burson]] \u2013 [[Bugs Bunny]] (in \"Buster and Babs Go Hawaiian\" and \"Best of Buster Day\"), [[Daffy Duck]] (in \"Two-Tone Town\"), [[Elmer Fudd]], [[Foghorn Leghorn]] (in \"Buster and Babs Go Hawaiian\"), [[Tasmanian Devil (Looney Tunes)|Tasmanian Devil]] (in \"Best of Buster Day\"), [[Pep\u00e9 Le Pew]]\n* [[Pat Buttram]] \u2013 Bicycle Bob\n* [[Hamilton Camp]] \u2013 Scottish Flea\n* [[Dan Castellaneta]] \u2013 Jeffries, Lars Thorwald\n* [[Jim Cummings]] \u2013 [[Shredder (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Iodizer]], [[Jack Nicholson]], Melvin the Monster, [[Mike Tyson]], Papa Flea\n* [[Tim Curry]] \u2013 Prince Charles, Reginald\n* [[Louise DuArt]] \u2013 [[Barbara Walters]]\n* [[Pat Fraley]] \u2013 Chef, Travel Agent\n* [[Stan Freberg]] \u2013 [[List of Looney Tunes and Merrie Melodies characters#The Three Bears|Junior Bear]], [[List of Looney Tunes and Merrie Melodies characters#Pete Puma|Pete Puma]]\n* [[Matt Frewer]] \u2013 Mac Duff (in \"Take Elmyra Please\" and \"Grandma's Dead\")\n* [[Soleil Moon Frye]] \u2013 Amanda Duff\n* [[June Foray]] \u2013 Granny, Witch Hazel (In \"Night Ghoulery\")\n* Ben Ryan Ganger \u2013 Duncan\n* [[Danny Gans]] \u2013 [[Donald Trump]], [[Johnny Carson]]\n* [[Joan Gerber]] \u2013 Gotcha Grabmore\n* [[Phillip Glasser]] \u2013 Pedro\n* [[Desir\u00e9e Goyette]] \u2013 Roxy\n* [[Edan Gross]] \u2013 Tyrone the Turtle\n* [[Phil Hartman]] \u2013 Octavius\n* [[Whitby Hertford]] \u2013 Duncan Duff, Fleo\n* John Hillner \u2013 [[Michigan J. Frog]]\n* [[Carol Kane]] \u2013 Ollie\n* [[Casey Kasem]] - Flakey Flakems\n* [[Jim MacGeorge]] - Announcer\n* [[James Mates]] - Narrator\n* [[Edie McClurg]] \u2013 Winnie Pig\n* Cindy McGee \u2013 Mary Melody (in \"Furrball Follies\")\n* [[Brian Stokes Mitchell]] \u2013 Vinnie\n* [[Robert Morse]] \u2013 Goopy Geer\n* [[Vincent Price]] \u2013 [[Edgar Allan Poe]]\n* [[Clive Revill]] \u2013 [[William Shakespeare]]\n* [[Andrea Romano (voice director)|Andrea Romano]] \u2013 [[Andrea Romano (voice director)|Andrea Romano]] the Magnificent\n* [[Roger Rose]] \u2013 [[David Letterman]], [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles|Ninja Turtle]]\n* [[Maggie Roswell]] \u2013 Mary Vain\n* [[Nathan Ruegger]] \u2013 Baby Plucky Duck\n* [[Fran Ryan]] \u2013 Grandma Duff\n* [[Jean Smart]] - Announcer\n* [[Steven Spielberg]] \u2013 Himself (in \"Buster and Babs Go Hawaiian\"), [[Roger Rabbit]]\n* [[Sally Struthers]] \u2013 Rhoda, Sandy Witch\n* [[B. J. Ward (actress)|B.J. Ward]] \u2013 Honey\n* [[Vernee Watson]] - Announcer, Joker\n* [[Billy West]] - Hamton Pig (only in video games - 1999-2002)\n* [[Jonathan Winters]] \u2013 Stanley Elephant, Wade Pig\n* [[Henny Youngman]] \u2013 Himself\n\n==Films and television specials==\nA feature-length [[film|movie]] was released [[direct-to-video]] in 1992, entitled ''[[Tiny Toon Adventures: How I Spent My Vacation]]''.<ref name=\"vacation\">Lenburg, p. 336. Retrieved 2007-06-27.</ref> This was later re-edited and aired as part of the series. The length of the movie is 73 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiny Toon Adventures: How I Spent My Vacation|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0105598/|work=The Internet Movie Database|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] aired ''It's a Wonderful Tiny Toons Christmas Special'' in prime time on December 6, 1992.<ref name=xmas>{{cite web|title=TV Listings for - December 6, 1992 - TV Tango|url=http://www.tvtango.com/listings/1992/12/06|publisher=TV Tango|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> This episode is a parody of ''[[It\u2019s a Wonderful Life]]''. Although the Christmas episode is called a special, it is only called this as it is Christmas-themed and is just a regular episode. ''The Tiny Toon Spring Break Special''<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiny Toons Spring Break|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0108343/|work=The Internet Movie Database|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> was aired on Fox during prime time on March 27, 1994.<ref name=springbreak/><ref name=sunday>{{cite web|title=TV Listings for - March 27, 1994 - TV Tango|url=http://www.tvtango.com/listings/1994/03/27|publisher=TV Tango|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> Fox aired ''Tiny Toons' Night Ghoulery''<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiny Toons' Night Ghoulery|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0123298/|work=The Internet Movie Database|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> in prime time on May 28, 1995.<ref name=may28>{{cite web|title=TV Listings for - May 28, 1995 - TV Tango|url=http://www.tvtango.com/listings/1995/05/28|publisher=TV Tango|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Spin-offs==\n{{Main|The Plucky Duck Show|Pinky, Elmyra & the Brain}}\nIn 1992, ''[[The Plucky Duck Show]]'' was produced as a spin-off for [[Fox Kids]], based on the character Plucky Duck. Except for the premiere episode, \"The Return of Batduck\", the show was composed entirely of recycled Plucky-centric episodes from ''Tiny Toon Adventures''.<ref name=\"spinoff1\">{{cite web|title=Trivia for \"The Plucky Duck Show\"|publisher=The Internet Movie Database|url=http://imdb.com/title/tt0103513/trivia|accessdate=2007-06-02}}{{Unreliable source?|date=January 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, a second spin-off, entitled ''[[Pinky, Elmyra & the Brain]]'', debuted on [[Kids' WB]]. This series featured the character Elmyra Duff as well as Pinky and the Brain, two other characters who were originally on ''[[Animaniacs]]'' before receiving their own spin-off series, also entitled ''[[Pinky and the Brain]]''. ''Pinky, Elmyra & the Brain'' picks up after ''Pinky and the Brain'' leaves off where Pinky and the Brain become Elmyra's pets after Brain accidentally destroys their original home, ACME Labs, during an experiment. ''Pinky, Elmyra & the Brain'' lasted for 13 episodes.\n\n==Response==\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Year\n! Category\n! Nominee\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[Daytime Emmy Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[18th Daytime Emmy Awards|1991]]\n| [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Children's Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program]]<ref name=\"emmy91\">{{cite web|title=Awards for \"Tiny Toon Adventures\"|publisher=The Internet Movie Database|url=http://imdb.com/title/tt0098929/awards|accessdate=2007-06-02}}</ref>\n| [[Steven Spielberg]], [[Tom Ruegger]], Ken Boyer, Art Leonardi, Art Vitello, [[Paul Dini]], and [[Sherri Stoner]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Music Direction and Composition<ref name=\"Awards for 'Tiny Toon Adventures'\">{{cite web|title=Awards for 'Tiny Toon Adventures'|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0098929/awards|work=The Internet Movie Database|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref>\n| [[William Ross (composer)|William Ross]] for \"Fields of Honey\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Original Song<ref name=\"Awards for 'Tiny Toon Adventures'\"/>\n| [[Bruce Broughton]], [[Wayne Kaatz]], and [[Tom Ruegger]] for the main title theme\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[19th Daytime Emmy Awards|1992]]\n| [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Children's Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program]]<ref name=\"emmy91\"/>\n| [[Steven Spielberg]], [[Tom Ruegger]], [[Sherri Stoner]], Rich Arons, and Art Leonardi\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Music Direction and Composition<ref name=\"Awards for 'Tiny Toon Adventures'\"/>\n| [[Mark Watters]] for \"The Love Disconnection\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Writing in an Animated Program<ref name=\"Awards for 'Tiny Toon Adventures'\"/>\n| Nicholas Hollander, [[Tom Ruegger]], [[Paul Dini]], and [[Sherri Stoner]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[20th Daytime Emmy Awards|1993]]\n| [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Children's Animated Program|Outstanding Animated Program]]<ref name=\"emmy91\"/>\n| [[Steven Spielberg]], [[Tom Ruegger]], [[Sherri Stoner]], Rich Arons, Byron Vaughns, Ken Boyer, Alfred Gimeno, and David West\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Music Direction and Composition\n| [[Steven Bramson]] for \u201cThe Horror of Slumber Party Mountain\u201d<ref name=\"Awards for 'Tiny Toon Adventures'\"/>\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n; '''[[Annie Awards]]''':\n:Nominated for Best Animated Television Program (1992)<ref name=\"Awards for 'Tiny Toon Adventures'\"/>\n:Nominated for Best Animated Television Program (1993)<ref name=\"Awards for 'Tiny Toon Adventures'\"/>\n\n; '''[[Emmy Awards]]''':\n:Nominated for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program (for Programming Less Than One Hour)|Outstanding Animated Program]] (teen [[Steven Spielberg]], [[Tom Ruegger]], [[Paul Dini]], [[Sherri Stoner]], Dave Marshall, Glen Kennedy, Rich Aarons) ([[43rd Primetime Emmy Awards|1991]])<ref name=\"Awards for 'Tiny Toon Adventures'\"/>\n\n; '''[[Young Artist Awards]]''':\n:Won award for Best New Cartoon Series (1989\u20131990)<ref name=\"youngartist\">{{cite web|title=Twelfth Annual Youth in Film Awards: 1989\u20131990|publisher=The Young Artist Foundation|url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms12.htm|accessdate=2007-06-02}}</ref>\n:Nominated for Outstanding Young Voice-Over in an Animated Series or Special ([[Whitby Hertford]]) (1991\u20131992)<ref name=\"youngartist2\">{{cite web|title=Fourteenth Annual Youth in Film Awards: 1991\u20131992|publisher=The Young Artist Foundation|url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms14.htm|accessdate=2007-06-02}}</ref>\n\n; '''[[Environmental Media Awards]]''':\n:Won EMA Award for Children's Animated series (for the episode ''Whales Tales'') (1991)<ref name=\"emmy91\"/>\n\nIn January 2009, IGN named ''Tiny Toons'' as the 41st in their Top 100 Animated TV Shows list.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tv.ign.com/top-100-animated-tv-series/41.html |title=Video Games, Wikis, Cheats, Walkthroughs, Reviews, News & Videos - IGN |website=Tv.ign.com |accessdate=2016-09-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211081204/http://tv.ign.com/top-100-animated-tv-series/41.html |archivedate=2009-02-11 }}</ref>\n\n==Merchandise==\n\n===Print===\n''Tiny Toon Adventures Magazine'', a quarterly children's magazine based on the series, debuted in October 1990. Issues #1\u20134 were published by [[DC Comics]], and issues #5\u20137 were released by Welsh Publishing Group. The final issue was cover-dated Spring 1992.<ref>[http://www.comicbookdb.com/title.php?ID=37392 The Comic Book Database: Tiny Toon Adventures Magazine]</ref> Also, various storybooks were published by the [[Little Golden Books|Little Golden Book]] company, including a few episode adaptations and some original stories (''Lost in the Fun House'' and ''Happy Birthday, Babs!''). ''Tiny Toon Adventures'' also had a comic book series made by [[Warner Bros.]] and DC. The characters also made occasional cameo appearances in the ''[[Animaniacs]]'', ''[[Freakazoid!]]'' and ''[[Pinky and the Brain]]'' comic books.{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}\n\n===Toys and video games===\n{{Main|List of Tiny Toon Adventures video games}}\nSince its debut, numerous [[video game]]s based on ''Tiny Toons'' have been released. There have been no less than nine titles based on the series released after its original television run and as recently as 2002. Many companies have held the development and publishing rights for the games, including [[Konami]] (during the 1990s), [[Atari]], [[NewKidCo]], [[Conspiracy Games]], [[Warthog Games Limited|Warthog]], [[Terraglyph Interactive Studios]], and [[Treasure Co. Ltd|Treasure]]. Toys for the series included plush dolls and plastic figures, primarily made by [[Playskool]].\n\n===Home media===\n''[[Tiny Toon Adventures: How I Spent My Vacation]]'' was released on [[DVD]] on August 21, 2012. There are currently no plans to release the two specials (''Spring Break'' and ''Night Ghoulery'') on [[DVD]].  In the early to mid-1990s, Warner Bros. had released several videos, including ''Tiny Toon Adventures: How I Spent My Vacation'' (a direct-to-video release which later aired as a four-part TV episode), ''Best of Buster and Babs'', ''Two-Tone Town'', ''Tiny Toons: Big Adventures'', ''Tiny Toons: Island Adventures'', ''Tiny Toons: Music Television'', ''Tiny Toons: Fiendishly Funny Adventures'', ''Tiny Toons: Night Ghoulery'' and ''It's a Wonderful Tiny Toons Christmas Special''.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!DVD name!!Ep #!!Release date!!Special Features!!Notes\n|-\n|Season 1 Volume 1|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |35|| {{Start date|2008|7|29}} || From Looney Tunes to Tiny Toons: A Wacky Evolution, featurette || Was released concurrently with the first season of ''[[Freakazoid!]]''. \"The Looney Beginning\" episode is uncut on the set.\n|-\n|Season 1 Volume 2 || style=\"text-align:center;\" |30 || {{Start date|2009|4|21}} || None, aside from trailers || Was released concurrently with the second season of ''[[Freakazoid!]]''. Two episodes are edited: \"Tiny Toons Music Television\" (a phone number gag was removed) and \"Son of the Wacko World of Sports\" (wraparounds and title cards were removed).{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n|-\n|Volume 3: Crazy Crew Rescues || style=\"text-align:center;\" |17 || {{Start date|2013|1|8}} || None, aside from trailers || The previously-banned episode \"Elephant Issues\" is included in this set. Initially when the set was announced, the content list did not contain the episode due to its controversial \"One Beer\" segment.<ref name=\"tvshowsondvd.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Tiny-Toon-Adventures-missing-episode-included/17575 |title=Tiny Toon Adventures DVD news: Missing episode, 'Elephant Issues,' to be included! |website=TVShowsOnDVD.com |date=2013-01-08 |accessdate=2016-09-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503155638/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Tiny-Toon-Adventures-missing-episode-included/17575 |archivedate=2016-05-03 }}</ref>\n|-\n|Volume 4: Looney Links || style=\"text-align:center;\" |16 || {{Start date|2013|5|28}} || None, aside from trailers || The original release contained a glitch which Warner Bros. fixed by the end of July. Also, \"Best of Buster Bunny Day\" is missing its second wraparound scene.{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n|}\n\n==History==\n\n===Preproduction===\nAccording to writer [[Paul Dini]], ''Tiny Toons'' originated as an idea by [[Terry Semel]], the then-president of [[Warner Bros.]], who wanted to \"inject new life into the [[Warner Bros. Animation]] department,\" and at the same time create a series with junior versions of [[List of Looney Tunes and Merrie Melodies characters|Looney Tunes characters]]. Semel proposed that the new series would be a show based on ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' where the characters were either young versions of the original ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' and ''[[Merrie Melodies]]'' characters or new characters as the offspring of the original characters.<ref name=\"creation\">{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Bob|title=NEW TOONS ON THE BLOCK: They're attending Acme Looniversity & hoping to graduate as classic cartoon characters|periodical=Comic Scene|issue=15|pages=33\u201339, 68|year=1990}}</ref> The idea of a series with the basis of younger and junior versions of cartoon characters was common at the time; the era in which ''Tiny Toons'' was produced for had such cartoons as ''[[Muppet Babies (1984 TV series)|Muppet Babies]]'', ''[[A Pup Named Scooby-Doo]]'', ''[[Tom & Jerry Kids]]'' and ''[[The Flintstones Kids]]''. [[Warner Bros.]] chose to do the same because Spielberg wanted to make a series similar to ''[[Looney Tunes]]'', as series producer/show-runner Tom Ruegger explained: \"Well, I think in [[Warner Bros.]] case, they had the opportunity to work with Steven Spielberg] on a project [...] But he didn't want to just work on characters that [[Chuck Jones]], [[Friz Freleng]], [[Robert McKimson|Bob McKimson]] and [[Bob Clampett]] made famous and created. He wanted to be involved with the creation of some ''new'' characters.\" The result was a series similar to ''Looney Tunes'' without the use of the same characters.<ref name=\"creation\"/>\n\nOn January 20, 1987,<ref name=\"collab2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,318258,00.html|title=SUFFERIN' SUCCOTASH! IT'S LOONEY TUNES, TAKE TWO|date=September 28, 1990|work=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref> the Warner Bros. Animation studio approached [[Steven Spielberg]] to collaborate with Semel and [[Warner Bros.]] head of licensing Dan Romanelli on Semel's ideas.<ref name=\"creation\"/> They eventually decided that the new characters would be similar to the ''[[Looney Tunes]]'' characters with no direct relation. However, ''Tiny Toons'' did not go into production then, nor was it even planned to be made for television; the series initially was to be a [[theatrical]] [[feature-length film]].<ref name=\"collab\"/><ref name=\"creation\"/>\n\nOn December 27, 1988, ''Tiny Toons'' was changed from a film to a television series, with [[Jean MacCurdy]] overseeing production of the first 65 episodes.<ref name=\"creation\"/> MacCurdy said that ''Tiny Toons'' was changed to a television series to \"reach a broader audience\".<ref name=\"collab\"/> For the series, MacCurdy hired [[Tom Ruegger]], who previously wrote cartoons for [[Filmation]] and [[Hanna-Barbera]], to be a producer.<ref name=\"creation\"/> In January 1989, Ruegger and writer [[Wayne Kaatz]] began developing the characters and the setting of \"Acme Acres\" with Spielberg.<ref name=\"creation\"/>\n\nOn January 9, 1989, [[Warner Bros. Animation]] chose its voice actors from over 1,200 auditions and put together its 100-person production staff.<ref name=\"collab\"/> On April 13, 1989, full production of series episodes began with five overseas animation houses and a total budget of $25 million.<ref name=\"collab\"/> The first 65 episodes of the series aired in syndication on 135 stations, beginning in September 1990.<ref name=\"airdate\">Lenburg, p. 336. Retrieved 2007-11-15.</ref> During that time, ''Tiny Toons'' was a huge success and got higher ratings than its ''[[The Disney Afternoon|Disney Afternoon]]'' competitors in some affiliates. After a successful run in syndication, Fox attained the rights for season 3. Production of the series halted in late 1992 to make way for ''[[Animaniacs]]'' to air the following year.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite encyclopedia|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|encyclopedia=The Encyclopedia of Animated Cartoons|edition=Second|title=Specials|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816038312/page/336 336\u2013337]|publisher=Checkmark Books|location=New York, New York|year=1999|isbn=0-8160-3831-7|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816038312/page/336}}\n* {{Cite encyclopedia|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|encyclopedia=The Encyclopedia of Animated Cartoons|edition=Second|title=Steven Spielberg Presents Tiny Toon Adventures [Television Series]|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816038312/page/521 521]|publisher=Checkmark Books|location=New York, New York|year=1999|isbn=0-8160-3831-7|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816038312/page/521}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Portal|Animation|Cartoon|1990s}}\n* {{IMDb title|0098929|Tiny Toon Adventures}}\n* {{bcdb |Warner_Bros_/Television/Tiny_Toon_Adventures/ |Tiny Toon Adventures }}\n* {{tv.com show|tiny-toon-adventures|Tiny Toon Adventures}}\n*[http://toonopedia.com/tinytoon.htm ''Tiny Toon Adventures''] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160517090404/http://www.toonopedia.com/tinytoon.htm Archived] from the original on December 7, 2017.\n\n{{Tiny Toon Adventures}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Children's Animated Program}}\n{{Looney Tunes & Merrie Melodies}}\n{{Warner Bros. animation and comics}}\n{{Fox Kids}}\n{{Kids' WB}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1990s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American daily animated television series]]\n[[Category:1990s American satirical television series]]\n[[Category:1990 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1992 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Animated Program winners]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:First-run syndicated television programs in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fox Kids original programming]]\n[[Category:Kids' WB original programs]]\n[[Category:Looney Tunes]]\n[[Category:Looney Tunes television series]]\n[[Category:Self-reflexive television]]\n[[Category:1990s American surreal comedy television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Amblin Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Television series by Warner Bros. Animation]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Tom Ruegger]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Tiny Toon Adventures| ]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about rabbits and hares]]\n", "name_user": "Makendo k", "label": "safe", "comment": "Inclusion of references, adjustment in the infobox and formatting of the article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiny_Toon_Adventures"}
{"title_page": "Morganza Spillway", "text_new": "[[Image:Morganza Spillway Aerial.jpg|thumb|300 px|The Morganza Spillway, between the [[Mississippi River]] and the [[Atchafalaya Basin]], shown while open in 1973. Water flows from the Mississippi (upper right) into the Morganza Floodway (lower left).]]\nThe '''Morganza Spillway''' or '''Morganza Control Structure''' is a flood-control structure in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Louisiana]] along the western bank of the [[Lower Mississippi River]] at river mile 280, near [[Morganza, Louisiana|Morganza]] in [[Pointe Coupee Parish]]. The spillway stands between the Mississippi and the '''Morganza Floodway''', which leads to the [[Atchafalaya Basin]] and the [[Atchafalaya River]] in south-central [[Louisiana]]. Its purpose is to divert water from the Mississippi River during major [[flood]] events by flooding the Atchafalaya Basin, including the Atchafalaya River and the Atchafalaya Swamp. The spillway and adjacent [[levee]]s also help prevent the Mississippi from changing its present course through the [[List of ports in the United States|major port cities]] of [[Baton Rouge]] and [[New Orleans]] to a new course down the Atchafalaya River to the [[Gulf of Mexico]]. The Morganza Spillway, operated by the [[US Army Corps of Engineers|U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]], was opened during the 1973 and 2011 [[Mississippi River floods]].<ref name='USACE'>{{cite web | url = http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/morganza.asp | title = Morganza Floodway | accessdate = 2011-05-08 | publisher = US Army Corps of Engineers | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111181513/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/morganza.asp |archivedate=January 11, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"AmericasWetlands\">{{cite web|title=Louisiana OLD RIVER CONTROL STRUCTURE and Mississippi river flood protection|url=http://www.americaswetlandresources.com/background_facts/detailedstory/LouisianaRiverControl.html|work=America's Wetland Resource Center|publisher=Loyola University's Center for Environmental Communication (LUCEC)}}</ref><ref name='Weeks'>{{cite web | url = http://www.johnweeks.com/river_mississippi/pages/lmiss24.html | title = Morganza Floodway | accessdate = 2011-05-08 | last = Weeks | first = John A.}}</ref><ref name=\"InteractiveMap\">{{cite web | url = http://www.mappingsupport.com/p/gmap4.php?q=https://sites.google.com/site/gmap4files/p/news/mississippi_course_change.txt&ll=30.417887,-91.201416&t=h&z=9&label=on | title = Will the Mississippi River change its course in 2011 to the red line? | accessdate = 2011-05-08 | publisher = Mappingsupport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Corps does dry run for river flooding. Drill gets agencies to work together.|author=Matt Scallan|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|page=1|date=March 16, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[Great Mississippi Flood of 1927]] was the most destructive [[river flood]] in the [[history of the United States]],<ref>[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/0501_river4.html Man v. Nature, National Geographic, May 2001] Accessed June 14, 2008</ref> in large part due to the [[Mississippi River]] swelling to {{convert|80|mi|km}} wide in spots.<ref name=\"Corps\">{{cite news |title=Corps Opens Morganza. Water unleashed into Atchafalaya Basin.|author=Paul Rioux|url=http://www.nola.com/environment/index.ssf/2011/05/flow_of_mississippi_river_floo.html|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]] |date=May 15, 2011 |accessdate=May 15, 2011}}</ref> To prevent a repeat of the Great Flood of 1927, and better control river flooding in general, [[U.S Congress|Congress]] passed the [[Flood Control Act of 1928]] to authorize the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] to build the [[Bonnet Carre Spillway]] (located {{convert|33|mi|km}} above [[New Orleans]] and completed in 1931),<ref>{{cite news|page=1|title=Corps slogs through test run at spillway. Opening this year appears unlikely.|author=Matt Scallan |url=http://www.nola.com/news/index.ssf/2008/04/as_water_rises_corps_practices.html|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|date=April 2, 2008|accessdate=May 15, 2011}}</ref> the [[Birds Point floodway]] in [[Missouri]], and the Morganza Floodway as part of the 1928 [[Mississippi River and Tributaries Project]].<ref name=\"Corps\"/>\n[[File:Gate of Morganza Floodway.jpg|right|thumb|180 px|One of the 125 gates on the tail bay side of the Morganza Floodway.]]\n\nConstruction of the levees that make up part of the Morganza Spillway began in the late 1930s.  The Morganza Control Structure portion of the project was completed in 1954<ref name=\"Corps\" /> and subsequently became incorporated into the [[Mississippi River Commission]]'s 1956 [[project design flood]],<ref>{{cite news|page=A1|title=Mississippi projects shield human lives. Levees just part of flood control.|author=Steven Ward|url=http://www.2theadvocate.com/news/18323544.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502004659/http://www.2theadvocate.com/news/18323544.html|archivedate=2008-05-02|newspaper=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)]]|date=April 28, 2008|accessdate=May 15, 2011}}</ref> which added the [[Old River Control Structure]] (ORCS) in 1963 to the protections used to prevent Mississippi River flood.<ref>{{cite news|page=A1|title=That water is on its way|author=Mike Hasten|url=http://www.thetowntalk.com/article/20110506/NEWS01/105060339/Gov-Jindal-warns-flooding-activates-National-Guard?odyssey=mod%7Cmostview|newspaper=[[Alexandria Daily Town Talk]]|date=May 6, 2011|accessdate=May 15, 2011}}{{dead link|date=April 2017}}</ref>  The [[Flood Control Act of 1965]] provided further regulation over the Morganza Spillway's role in Mississippi River flood prevention. A concrete pit called a [[hydraulic jump|stilling basin]] was added at the Morganza Spillway in 1977 \"to provide erosion protection after the velocity of water pouring through the open bays during a 1973 flood caused severe [[Bridge scour|scour]]ing of the land behind the bays.\"<ref>[ftp://opinions.ca5.uscourts.gov/unpub/94/94-30493.0.wpd.pdf Minor v. United States]{{Dead link|date=December 2015}}, [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]] (No. 94-30493) (January 17, 1995).</ref>\n\n==Design and construction==\nThe Morganza Spillway, a {{convert|4159|ft|m|adj=on}} ''controlled'' [[spillway]] using a set of flood gates to control the volume of water entering the Morganza Floodway from the Mississippi River, consists of a concrete [[weir]], two [[sluice]] gates, seventeen scour indicators, and 125 gated openings which can allow up to {{convert|600000|cuft/s|abbr=off|lk=on}} of water to be diverted from the Mississippi River into the Atchafalaya Basin during major floods. The project was completed in 1954.\n\nA highway ([[Louisiana Highway 1|Louisiana Route&nbsp;1]]) and the [[Kansas City Southern Railway]] cross the structure\n\nThe Corps of Engineers maintains the structures and, in times of flood, monitors their piers for scouring and stability. The Corps of Engineers has two 25-ton cranes used to lift and lower the flood gates. The cranes roll on special tracks next to the roadway, enabling the operators to open or shut any spillway gate or perform maintenance while the roadway is in use.\n\n==Operation during floods==\nThe land on both sides of the Morganza Control Structure is above normal river water levels, and usually dry. In order for water to reach the spillway, the Mississippi must first rise well above its [[flood stage]], overtopping its banks. The Corps of Engineers considers opening the Morganza Spillway when the flow of the Mississippi at [[Red River Landing, Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Mississippi River at Red River Landing (01120)|url=http://www2.mvr.usace.army.mil/WaterControl/stationinfo2.cfm?sid=01120&fid=BTRL1&dt=S|date=May 7, 2011|publisher=United States Army Corps of Engineers|accessdate=10 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927153416/http://www2.mvr.usace.army.mil/WaterControl/stationinfo2.cfm?sid=01120&fid=BTRL1&dt=S|archivedate=27 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Daily State and Discharge Data - Water Control - New Orleans District|url=http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/eng/edhd/dailystagedisplay.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040514060639/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/eng/edhd/dailystagedisplay.asp|archivedate=2004-05-14|publisher=U.S. Army Corps of Engineers|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> is greater than {{convert|1500000|cuft/s|abbr=on}} and rising.<ref name='USACE' />\n\n[[File:1986 Design Flows.gif|thumb|left|250 px|A diagram that shows flows during a project design flood.|A diagram that depicts river flows flow through the Morganza Spillway to the Red and Atchafalaya Rivers associated with a [[project design flood]], which is the hypothetical \"maximum probable\" flood of the Mississippi River, as estimated by the Corps of Engineers.  The water channel flow rates are listed in cubic feet per second.]]\n\nWater from the Mississippi is normally diverted into the Atchafalaya Basin at only one place, the [[Old River Control Structure]] (ORCS), in use since 1963, where floodgates are routinely used to redirect the Mississippi's flow into the Atchafalaya River such that the volume of the two rivers is split 70%/30%, respectively, as measured at the latitude of [[Red River Landing]]. During the 1973 Mississippi flood, the ORCS was being damaged due to high flow rates, leading to the opening of the Morganza Spillway to help relieve this pressure. Subsequently, the nearby Old River Control Auxiliary Structure (ORCAS) was constructed, adding additional floodgates for use during major floods.\n\nThe Morganza Spillway, about {{convert|30|mi|km}} downriver from ORCS and ORCAS, is designed for emergency use to divert additional water from the Mississippi River into the Morganza floodway, which merges downstream with the Atchafalaya floodway before entering the Gulf. Diversion of water from the Mississippi's main channel has the effect of lowering water level in the Mississippi downstream of the spillway, helping to relieve stress on levees and other flood control structures both upstream and down. Besides controlling flooding in a given event, the system is also designed to prevent the Mississippi River from permanently altering course down the Atchafalaya River, bypassing Baton Rouge and New Orleans.<ref name='USACE' /><ref name=\"AmericasWetlands\" /><ref name='Weeks' /><ref name=\"InteractiveMap\" />\n\nWater that passes the Morganza Spillway first enters the Morganza Floodway, which extends from the spillway at the Mississippi River south to the East Atchafalaya River levee. The floodway, {{convert|20|mi}} long and {{convert|5|mi}} wide, includes a stilling basin, an approach channel, an outlet channel, and two guide [[levee]]s.<ref name='USACE' /> From there, diverted water enters the [[Atchafalaya River Basin]] Floodway near [[Krotz Springs, Louisiana]],<ref name='USACE' /> and continues to the Gulf of Mexico.\n\nIn an extreme flood event, a major release of water from the Morganza Spillway into the Morganza Floodway and Atchafalaya Basin inundates not only the floodways themselves (between their levees), but extensive additional areas of southern Louisiana throughout the [[Atchafalaya Basin]]. In such an event, the water level of the Mississippi, high enough to overtop the Spillway, would already be flooding some areas in the Basin downstream of the spillway, due to increased flow through the ORCS and the ORCAS, as well as possible overtopping of levees near the spillway.<ref name=\"2008leveetopped\" /> This flooding, plus any additional water from a Morganza Spillway release, together determine the total extent of flooding throughout the Atchafalaya Basin during a major Mississippi River flood.\n\nAt risk in the Atchafalaya Basin are [[Morgan City, Louisiana|Morgan City]] (population 13,500), various smaller populated places, many farms, thousands of oil and gas wells, and considerable swampland. Inhabitants know that the region is a natural [[floodplain]], and the Corps of Engineers issues written notices annually to all interests reminding them of the possibility that it might open the spillway and flood the area.  Any decision to open the spillway must be carefully planned to give ample warning and protect life and property.   Part of that planning process includes the Corps' preparation of maps known as \"inundation scenarios\" so that interested parties can discuss how much water, if any, should be allowed through the spillway.<ref name='USACE' /><ref name=TP1>{{cite web|last=Schliefstein|first=Mark|title=Record high river likely to require opening of Morganza Spillway next week (May 4, 2011, revised May 9, 2011)|url=http://www.nola.com/weather/index.ssf/2011/05/record_high_river_likely_to_re.html|publisher=The Times-Picayune (New Orleans)|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=TP2>{{cite web|last=Schliefstein|first=Mark|title=Morganza Spillway might be opened to ease swollen Mississippi River (May 8, 2011, revised May 9, 2011)|url=http://www.nola.com/weather/index.ssf/2011/05/morganza_spillway_might_be_ope.html|publisher=The Times-Picayune (New Orleans)|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.thenewsstar.com/article/20110510/NEWS01/105100316 Morganza Spillway expected to open soon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514001342/http://www.thenewsstar.com/article/20110510/NEWS01/105100316 |date=2011-05-14 }}, ''The News Star'': May 9, 2011, Mike Hasten</ref><ref>[http://www.batonrougetoday.com/2011/05/06/gov-jindal-asks-army-corps-to-release-map-outlining-impact-of-possible-opening-of-morganza-spillway-says-state-continues-to-prepare-for-flooding/ Gov. Jindal Asks Army Corps to Release Map Outlining Impact of Possible Opening of Morganza Spillway, Says State Continues to Prepare for Flooding], ''Baton Rouge Today'': May 6, 2011. {{Dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=Trading>{{cite news|author1=Vastag, Brian |author2=Lisa Rein |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Trading one deluge for another? As panic rises with the Mississippi, engineers consider flooding farms to protect two La. cities|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=May 12, 2011| page=Pages A1 & A6}}</ref><ref name=Bloomberg>{{cite web|author1=Sullivan, Brian K. |author2=Leela Landress |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Morganza Spillway to open as river flow rises to threshold|url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-05-14/morganza-spillway-to-open-as-river-flow-rises-to-threshold.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110804183328/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-05-14/morganza-spillway-to-open-as-river-flow-rises-to-threshold.html|archivedate=2011-08-04|publisher=Bloomberg Businessweek|accessdate=15 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Daniels|first=Ronald Joel|title=On Risk and Disaster: Lessons from Hurricane Katrina|year=2006|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|page=44}}</ref><ref name='CorpsInundMap'>{{cite web|title=Corps Releases Inundation Map|url=http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/news/view.asp?ID=461|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110729011745/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/news/view.asp?ID=461|archivedate=2011-07-29|date = 7 May 2011|work=News Release|publisher=U.S. Army Corps of Engineers|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring both moderate and severe floods of the Mississippi, the [[Bonnet Carr\u00e9 Spillway]] can also be opened to help protect New Orleans, many parts of which are below sea level. The Bonnet Carr\u00e9 Spillway, built after the [[Great Mississippi Flood of 1927]], is located well downstream of Morganza, where the Mississippi River approaches [[Lake Pontchartrain]] near New Orleans. The Corps uses Bonnet Carr\u00e9 to divert floodwaters into the lake in order to protect the levees near New Orleans.\n\nIntegrity of the Morganza Spillway, the Old River Control Structure, and nearby levees is essential to prevent the Mississippi from diverting its main channel into the Atchafalaya Basin.<ref>see [[2011 Mississippi River floods#Risk of major course change in the Lower Mississippi River|\"Risk of major course change in the Lower Mississippi River\"]] for further discussion</ref>\n\n== Flood events and the Morganza Spillway ==\nSince its completion in 1954, the Morganza Spillway has been opened twice, in 1973 and 2011. The Morganza Spillway was also considered for opening during other major floods of the Lower Mississippi River.\n\n===First opening of gates (1973)===\nOn April 17, 1973, in order to lower the water level of the Mississippi River and relieve pressure on the Old River Control Structure, the Corps of Engineers opened 42 of the 125 steel gates of the Morganza Spillway for the first time since its completion, allowing about half of its maximum designed flowrate to pass from the Mississippi into the Atchafalaya Basin. The spillway received minor scouring and slight damage to the stilling basin, and substantial flooding occurred in the Atchafalaya Basin. After the 1973 flood, the structure was restored to its original condition.<ref name='USACE' /><ref name='Weeks' /><ref name=\"Engineers\">{{cite news|title=Engineers Open Steel Gate of Morganza Spillway|page=93|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=April 18, 1973}}</ref><ref name=\"Community\">{{cite news|title=Community effort helps farmers. Levee built to protect land from flooding.|author=Amy Wold|newspaper=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)]]|page=B1|date=March 27, 2008|accessdate=May 15, 2011|url=http://www.2theadvocate.com/news/17041411.html?c=1290013583745}}{{Dead link|date=December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Gates left closed in floods of 1983, 1993, 1997, 2008, and 2016===\nThe issue of opening the gates to keep the Mississippi in its current place was next raised in May 1983.<ref>{{cite news|title=Along The Levee, The River Is Rising|author=Julia Cass|newspaper=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]|page=A1|date=May 27, 1983}}</ref> Although the gates were not opened, [[Louisiana Highway 1]] running across the spillway was closed, and the Corps of Engineers built a {{convert|12|ft|m|adj=on}} ring dike and put a blanket of earth across a section of the spillway to contain water pouring underneath it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cold Grips Midwest As More Floods Swamp Texas, Salt Lake City|author=United Press International|newspaper=[[Miami Herald]]|page=A4|date=June 7, 1983}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Great Mississippi and Missouri Rivers Flood of 1993|Great Mississippi and Missouri Rivers Flood in 1993]], officials decided to leave the gates of the Morganza Floodway closed.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Flood Of 1993|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|page=B6|date=July 10, 1993}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1997, the river water flow at [[Baton Rouge]] reached {{convert|10600000|gal|cuft|abbr=on}} ({{convert|10600000|gal|m3|disp=output only}}) per second.<ref name=\"Shipping\">{{cite news|title=Shipping Perilous, B.R. Levees Threatened|author=Chris Gray|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|page=A1|date=March 21, 1997}}</ref> However, the flow rate never reached the threshold of {{convert|11200000|gal|cuft|abbr=on}} ({{convert|11200000|gal|m3|disp=output only}}) per second for opening Morganza,<ref name=\"Shipping\"/> and residents of [[Sicily Island, Louisiana]], became angry that the spillway was not opened to prevent flooding in their homes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Home Not Flooded? Stay Out Of Shelter|author=Leslie Zganjar|newspaper=[[Seattle Times]]|page=A8|date=March 21, 1997|accessdate=May 15, 2011|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970321&slug=2529854}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Using Morganza Endangers Business, Homes, Wildlife|author=Mark Schleifstein And Joan Treadway|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|page=A1|date=March 22, 1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=River Still Making Trouble Corps Snares Spillway Boater|author=Rhonda Bell|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|page=A1|date=March 23, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn March\u2013April 2008, officials considered but declined to open the spillway gates.<ref name=\"Community\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Gov. Jindal Holds Press Conference To Give Update On Rising Waters & Parishes In State Of Emergency With GOHSEP, Officials|author=Melissa Sellers|newspaper=US State News|date=April 6, 2008|accessdate=May 15, 2011|url=http://gohsep.la.gov/archive/2008/jindalriswaterrelease040608.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916093845/http://gohsep.la.gov/archive/2008/jindalriswaterrelease040608.htm|archivedate=2011-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=State, federal officials bracing for continued high water|author=M. Hasten|newspaper=[[The Times (Shreveport)]]|page=B05|date=April 7, 2008}}</ref>  While the spillway gates remained closed then, flooding occurred in the Morganza forebay when the Mississippi River crested higher than the potato ridge levee at the forebay entrance. Local residents and [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] troops attempted to add height to the permanent levee by building a supplemental [[sandbag]] levee on top of it. However, additional rainfall raised the flood crest higher than even the supplemental sandbags, sending floodwaters over these levees into {{convert|3000|acres}} of cropland located within the floodway.<ref name=\"2008leveetopped\">[http://midsouthfarmer.com/story.aspx/water/over/the/levee/in/louisiana/14/16637 Water Over the Levee in Louisiana: 3,000 acres of wheat acres hurt] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110821231242/http://midsouthfarmer.com/story.aspx/water/over/the/levee/in/louisiana/14/16637 |date=2011-08-21 }}, ''Midsouth Farmer'', April 8, 2008.</ref>\nIn the spring of 2016, the Corps considered opening the spillway but the forecast was lowered for the crest of the Mississippi River at Red River Landing, so the gates were left closed.\n\n=== Second opening of gates (2011) ===\n{{main|2011 Mississippi River floods}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; clear:right;margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;\"\n|+Flooding Scenarios<ref name='USACE NOD'>{{cite web | url = http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/missriver.asp | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081009210808/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/missriver.asp | archivedate = 2008-10-09 | title = The Mississippi River | accessdate = 2011-05-12 | date = 2011-05-09 | publisher = United States Army Corps of Engineers}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:NO District Inundation Spring May 2011.jpg|thumb|200px|Anticipated inundation from Scenario&nbsp;1]]\n|-\n|[[File:NODInundationMay2011Scenario1a.jpg|thumb|200px|Anticipated inundation from Scenario&nbsp;1a]]\n|-\n|[[File:NODInundationMay2011Scenario2.jpg|thumb|200px|Anticipated inundation from Scenario&nbsp;2]]\n|-\n|[[File:NODInundationMay2011Scenario3.jpg|thumb|200px|Anticipated inundation from Scenario&nbsp;3]]\n|}\nThe 2011 Mississippi River floods began to become serious in April. In response, the Corps first analyzed the flooding, and then opened the spillway in a controlled manner. The Corps studied four flooding scenarios, all of which assumed the Bonnet Carr\u00e9 Spillway would be concurrently operating at full capacity (100%).\n*Scenario 1: Open the Morganza Spillway to half (50%) of its maximum capacity, which would divert {{convert|300000|cuft/s}} of water.\n*Scenario 1a: Open the Morganza Spillway to one-quarter (25%) of its maximum capacity, which would divert {{convert|150000|cuft/s}} of water.\n*Scenario 2: Do not open the Morganza Spillway, and keep the Old River Control Structure (ORCS) at its routine operating level of only 30% of the Mississippi's flow;  no additional water would be diverted\n*Scenario 3: Do not open the Morganza Spillway, and open the ORCS somewhat more, which would divert an extra {{convert|150000|cuft/s}} of water.\n\nFollowing this analysis, which showed that extensive flooding was expected in the Atchafalaya Basin regardless of the choice made regarding the Morganza Spillway, the Corps decided to start the 2011 diversion by opening the spillway a bit less than described in scenario 1a (21%, not 25%)<ref name=\"NOLAFirstGate\">[http://www.nola.com/environment/index.ssf/2011/05/morganza_floodway_opens_to_div.html Morganza Floodway opens to divert Mississippi River away from Baton Rouge, New Orleans | NOLA.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nThe [[Governor]] of Louisiana, [[Bobby Jindal]], had meanwhile sent a letter on May 4, 2011, to [[Robert Gates]], the [[United States Secretary of Defense]], requesting that the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] be deployed under [[Title 32 of the United States Code]] status to respond to record water levels in Louisiana, where there was \"a significant probability that the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers [would] open the Morganza Spillway for the first time since 1973.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Governor Jindal Sends Letter To Dept. Of Defense Requesting National Guard|newspaper=States News Service (released by the office of the governor of Louisiana)|date=May 4, 2011|accessdate=May 15, 2011|url=http://www.katc.com/news/governor-jindal-sends-letter-to-dept-of-defense-requesting-national-guard/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314030603/http://www.katc.com/news/governor-jindal-sends-letter-to-dept-of-defense-requesting-national-guard/|archivedate=2012-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThe second opening of the Morganza Spillway began with the lifting of a single floodgate on May 14, 2011. Diversion of {{convert|125000|cuft/s}} of water from the Mississippi River to the Atchafalaya Basin was planned during this event, with the structure operating at about 21% of its capacity.  This diversion was deemed necessary to protect levees and prevent major flooding in Baton Rouge and New Orleans, with the tradeoff of creating possibly severe flooding in the Atchafalaya Basin.<ref name='USACE' /><ref>[http://thewatchers.adorraeli.com/2011/05/14/morganza-spillway-about-to-open/ The Watchers - US 2011 Great Flood: Morganza spillway about to open<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nBy May 18, 2011, a total of 17 gates (the largest number for the 2011 event) had been opened by the Corps of Engineers. The Corps estimated the flow rate at {{convert|114000|cuft/s|abbr=on}}. However, on May 25, new estimates from the [[U.S. Geologic Survey]] (USGS) described a much higher rate of {{convert|172000|cuft/s|abbr=on}}, resulting in the closure of 3 bays by May 26, and additional closures by May 29, bringing the total to 11 bays with an estimated diversion rate of {{convert|120000|cuft/s|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"close-bays-whoops\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/news/view.asp?ID=482 | title=Corps begins to close bays on Morganza Floodway | publisher=US Army Corps of Engineers, Team New Orleans | date=May 26, 2011 | accessdate=May 29, 2011 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812074410/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/news/view.asp?ID=482 | archivedate=August 12, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"USACoE-pace\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/morganza.asp | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514001802/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/morganza.asp | archivedate=2011-05-14 | title=Morganza Floodway Opening Pace: 2011 | publisher=US Army Corps of Engineers, Team New Orleans | date=May 29, 2011 | accessdate=May 29, 2011}}</ref> The Corps continued to evaluate the flow and close additional bays as appropriate. By June 6, the number of open gates had been reduced to seven,<ref>[http://www.wafb.com/story/14846370/only-7-bays-remain-open-at-morganza-spillway WAFB: Only 7 Bays Remain Open at Morganze Spillway]</ref> and by June 8, only two gates were still open.<ref name=\"USACoE-pace\" /> All bays were closed on July 7, 2011.\n\nThe Corps had estimated that it would take opening one-fourth of the spillway\u2019s 125 bays \u2014 or 31 bays \u2014 to control the flow of the river through Baton Rouge in response to a forecast crest of {{convert|45|ft|m}} anticipated on Tuesday, May 17, 2011, which must remain below {{convert|1500000|cuft/s|abbr=on}} of water per second through Baton Rouge to ensure the integrity of the levee system.<ref>{{cite news|last=KENNEDY|first=KATIE|title=Planning for high water|url=http://www.2theadvocate.com/news/Planning-for-high-water.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518231217/http://www.2theadvocate.com/news/Planning-for-high-water.html|archivedate=2011-05-18|accessdate=15 May 2011|newspaper=The Advocate|date=15 May 2011}}</ref> Since Morganza never operated above {{convert|172000|cuft/s|abbr=on}}, the flooding in the Atchafalaya Basin was considerably lower than had been anticipated during the initial estimates of {{convert|300000|cuft/s|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"close-bays-whoops\" /> By May 29, the Corps had also opened 330 of the 350 bays of the [[Bonnet Carr\u00e9 Spillway]] located near New Orleans.<ref name=\"USACoE-pace\" />\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Morganza Floodway opened in Louisiana seen from Air.jpg|<small>Aerial photograph of the first bay opening on the Morganza Floodway on 14 May 2011. The Mississippi River is in the upper left background, and the Atchafalaya Floodway to the right.</small>\nImage:Morganza Floodway Travel Times May 2011.jpg|Water travel time down the Morganza Floodway after the May 14, 2011 opening.\nImage:May 2011 Morganza Spillway Opens in Louisiana.jpg|Natural-colour satellite image of the Floodway on May 15, 2011.\nImage:May 2011 Morganza Spillway Opens in Louisiana (False Colour).jpg|False colour satellite image of the Floodway on May 15, 2011.\n</gallery>\n\n=== Third opening of gates (2019; cancelled) ===\n\n''Main article: [[Mississippi River floods of 2019]]''\n\nOn Wednesday May 22, 2019, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers announced that due to the extended flood event on the Mississippi River, which had been above flood stage since January 2019, they were anticipating the third opening of the Morganza Spillway. An anticipated further river rise stoked fears that the Mississippi River waters would overtop the spillway, which would destroy the structure. The possible opening could happen as early as June 2, 2019. On Monday May 27, 2019, the Army Corps of Engineers officially announced it would open Morganza on Sunday, June 2, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/Media/News-Releases/Article/1858495/usace-to-operate-morganza-control-structure/|title=USACE to operate Morganza Control Structure|website=New Orleans District|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the US Army Corps of Engineers New Orleans issued a press release on May 30, 2019, announcing the postponement of the opening of the Morganza Spillway until June 6, 2019; ultimately the spillway was never opened in 2019. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/Media/News-Releases/Article/1861810/update-operation-of-the-morganza-floodway-postponed/fbclid/IwAR20FuFYBdvtB5k82OL9o_4rCSGeBx6xsOO4Tqgug9MNzqd2MS2nYGJCS6U/fbclid/IwAR0P1dRoUIArOU1ssjsVCLyr3Unh7rMZ_Vu9eJwKTEsdW2g1j9Yfcrz5Vx4/|title=UPDATE: OPERATION OF THE MORGANZA FLOODWAY POSTPONED|website=New Orleans District|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref>  The opening was later postponed again to June 9, then indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/Media/News-Releases/Article/1864707/update-operation-of-the-morganza-floodway-postponed/|title=UPDATE: OPERATION OF THE MORGANZA FLOODWAY POSTPONED|website=New Orleans District|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/Media/News-Releases/Article/1868632/update-operation-of-the-morganza-floodway-postponed/|title=UPDATE: OPERATION OF THE MORGANZA FLOODWAY POSTPONED|website=New Orleans District|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[West Atchafalaya Floodway]]\n*The \"Atchafalaya\" section of the book ''[[The Control of Nature]]'' by [[John McPhee]].  {{ISBN|0-374-12890-1}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=7366074n Army Engineers Open Morganza Spillway]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Khjkpkz7iOU Morganza Spillway Fish Jumping through Gates]\n*For other images of the Morganza Control Structure in operation during the 2011 flood, see the [https://www.flickr.com/photos/37671998@N05/sets/72157626602502997/ U.S. Army Corps of Engineers Flickr page].\n\n{{coord|30.7766|-91.6199|region:US-LA_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Pointe Coupee Parish, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:United States Army Corps of Engineers]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Morganza Spillway Aerial.jpg|thumb|300 px|The Morganza Spillway, between the [[Mississippi River]] and the [[Atchafalaya Basin]], shown while open in 1973. Water flows from the Mississippi (upper right) into the Morganza Floodway (lower left).]]\nThe '''Morganza Spillway''' or '''Morganza Control Structure''' is a flood-control structure in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Louisiana]] along the western bank of the [[Lower Mississippi River]] at river mile 280, near [[Morganza, Louisiana|Morganza]] in [[Pointe Coupee Parish]]. The spillway stands between the Mississippi and the '''Morganza Floodway''', which leads to the [[Atchafalaya Basin]] and the [[Atchafalaya River]] in south-central [[Louisiana]]. Its purpose is to divert water from the Mississippi River during major [[flood]] events by flooding the Atchafalaya Basin, including the Atchafalaya River and the Atchafalaya Swamp. The spillway and adjacent [[levee]]s also help prevent the Mississippi from changing its present course through the [[List of ports in the United States|major port cities]] of [[Baton Rouge]] and [[New Orleans]] to a new course down the Atchafalaya River to the [[Gulf of Mexico]]. The Morganza Spillway, operated by the [[US Army Corps of Engineers|U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]], was opened during the 1973 and 2011 [[Mississippi River floods]].<ref name='USACE'>{{cite web | url = http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/morganza.asp | title = Morganza Floodway | accessdate = 2011-05-08 | publisher = US Army Corps of Engineers | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111181513/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/morganza.asp |archivedate=January 11, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"AmericasWetlands\">{{cite web|title=Louisiana OLD RIVER CONTROL STRUCTURE and Mississippi river flood protection|url=http://www.americaswetlandresources.com/background_facts/detailedstory/LouisianaRiverControl.html|work=America's Wetland Resource Center|publisher=Loyola University's Center for Environmental Communication (LUCEC)}}</ref><ref name='Weeks'>{{cite web | url = http://www.johnweeks.com/river_mississippi/pages/lmiss24.html | title = Morganza Floodway | accessdate = 2011-05-08 | last = Weeks | first = John A.}}</ref><ref name=\"InteractiveMap\">{{cite web | url = http://www.mappingsupport.com/p/gmap4.php?q=https://sites.google.com/site/gmap4files/p/news/mississippi_course_change.txt&ll=30.417887,-91.201416&t=h&z=9&label=on | title = Will the Mississippi River change its course in 2011 to the red line? | accessdate = 2011-05-08 | publisher = Mappingsupport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Corps does dry run for river flooding. Drill gets agencies to work together.|author=Matt Scallan|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|page=1|date=March 16, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[Great Mississippi Flood of 1927]] was the most destructive [[river flood]] in the [[history of the United States]],<ref>[http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/0501_river4.html Man v. Nature, National Geographic, May 2001] Accessed June 14, 2008</ref> in large part due to the [[Mississippi River]] swelling to {{convert|80|mi|km}} wide in spots.<ref name=\"Corps\">{{cite news |title=Corps Opens Morganza. Water unleashed into Atchafalaya Basin.|author=Paul Rioux|url=http://www.nola.com/environment/index.ssf/2011/05/flow_of_mississippi_river_floo.html|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]] |date=May 15, 2011 |accessdate=May 15, 2011}}</ref> To prevent a repeat of the Great Flood of 1927, and better control river flooding in general, [[U.S Congress|Congress]] passed the [[Flood Control Act of 1928]] to authorize the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] to build the [[Bonnet Carre Spillway]] (located {{convert|33|mi|km}} above [[New Orleans]] and completed in 1931),<ref>{{cite news|page=1|title=Corps slogs through test run at spillway. Opening this year appears unlikely.|author=Matt Scallan |url=http://www.nola.com/news/index.ssf/2008/04/as_water_rises_corps_practices.html|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|date=April 2, 2008|accessdate=May 15, 2011}}</ref> the [[Birds Point floodway]] in [[Missouri]], and the Morganza Floodway as part of the 1928 [[Mississippi River and Tributaries Project]].<ref name=\"Corps\"/>\n[[File:Gate of Morganza Floodway.jpg|right|thumb|180 px|One of the 125 gates on the tail bay side of the Morganza Floodway.]]\n\nConstruction of the levees that make up part of the Morganza Spillway began in the late 1930s.  The Morganza Control Structure portion of the project was completed in 1954<ref name=\"Corps\" /> and subsequently became incorporated into the [[Mississippi River Commission]]'s 1956 [[project design flood]],<ref>{{cite news|page=A1|title=Mississippi projects shield human lives. Levees just part of flood control.|author=Steven Ward|url=http://www.2theadvocate.com/news/18323544.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502004659/http://www.2theadvocate.com/news/18323544.html|archivedate=2008-05-02|newspaper=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)]]|date=April 28, 2008|accessdate=May 15, 2011}}</ref> which added the [[Old River Control Structure]] (ORCS) in 1963 to the protections used to prevent Mississippi River flood.<ref>{{cite news|page=A1|title=That water is on its way|author=Mike Hasten|url=http://www.thetowntalk.com/article/20110506/NEWS01/105060339/Gov-Jindal-warns-flooding-activates-National-Guard?odyssey=mod%7Cmostview|newspaper=[[Alexandria Daily Town Talk]]|date=May 6, 2011|accessdate=May 15, 2011}}{{dead link|date=April 2017}}</ref>  The [[Flood Control Act of 1965]] provided further regulation over the Morganza Spillway's role in Mississippi River flood prevention. A concrete pit called a [[hydraulic jump|stilling basin]] was added at the Morganza Spillway in 1977 \"to provide erosion protection after the velocity of water pouring through the open bays during a 1973 flood caused severe [[Bridge scour|scour]]ing of the land behind the bays.\"<ref>[ftp://opinions.ca5.uscourts.gov/unpub/94/94-30493.0.wpd.pdf Minor v. United States]{{Dead link|date=December 2015}}, [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit]] (No. 94-30493) (January 17, 1995).</ref>\n\n==Design and construction==\nThe Morganza Spillway, a {{convert|4159|ft|m|adj=on}} ''controlled'' [[spillway]] using a set of flood gates to control the volume of water entering the Morganza Floodway from the Mississippi River, consists of a concrete [[weir]], two [[sluice]] gates, seventeen scour indicators, and 125 gated openings which can allow up to {{convert|600000|cuft/s|abbr=off|lk=on}} of water to be diverted from the Mississippi River into the Atchafalaya Basin during major floods. The project was completed in 1954.\n\nA highway ([[Louisiana Highway 1|Louisiana Route&nbsp;1]]) and the [[Kansas City Southern Railway]] cross the structure\n\nThe Corps of Engineers maintains the structures and, in times of flood, monitors their piers for scouring and stability. The Corps of Engineers has two 25-ton cranes used to lift and lower the flood gates. The cranes roll on special tracks next to the roadway, enabling the operators to open or shut any spillway gate or perform maintenance while the roadway is in use.\n\n==Operation during floods==\nThe land on both sides of the Morganza Control Structure is above normal river water levels, and usually dry. In order for water to reach the spillway, the Mississippi must first rise well above its [[flood stage]], overtopping its banks. The Corps of Engineers considers opening the Morganza Spillway when the flow of the Mississippi at [[Red River Landing, Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Mississippi River at Red River Landing (01120)|url=http://www2.mvr.usace.army.mil/WaterControl/stationinfo2.cfm?sid=01120&fid=BTRL1&dt=S|date=May 7, 2011|publisher=United States Army Corps of Engineers|accessdate=10 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927153416/http://www2.mvr.usace.army.mil/WaterControl/stationinfo2.cfm?sid=01120&fid=BTRL1&dt=S|archivedate=27 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Daily State and Discharge Data - Water Control - New Orleans District|url=http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/eng/edhd/dailystagedisplay.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040514060639/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/eng/edhd/dailystagedisplay.asp|archivedate=2004-05-14|publisher=U.S. Army Corps of Engineers|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref> is greater than {{convert|1500000|cuft/s|abbr=on}} and rising.<ref name='USACE' />\n\n[[File:1986 Design Flows.gif|thumb|left|250 px|A diagram that shows flows during a project design flood.|A diagram that depicts river flows flow through the Morganza Spillway to the Red and Atchafalaya Rivers associated with a [[project design flood]], which is the hypothetical \"maximum probable\" flood of the Mississippi River, as estimated by the Corps of Engineers.  The water channel flow rates are listed in cubic feet per second.]]\n\nWater from the Mississippi is normally diverted into the Atchafalaya Basin at only one place, the [[Old River Control Structure]] (ORCS), in use since 1963, where floodgates are routinely used to redirect the Mississippi's flow into the Atchafalaya River such that the volume of the two rivers is split 70%/30%, respectively, as measured at the latitude of [[Red River Landing]]. During the 1973 Mississippi flood, the ORCS was being damaged due to high flow rates, leading to the opening of the Morganza Spillway to help relieve this pressure. Subsequently, the nearby Old River Control Auxiliary Structure (ORCAS) was constructed, adding additional floodgates for use during major floods.\n\nThe Morganza Spillway, about {{convert|30|mi|km}} downriver from ORCS and ORCAS, is designed for emergency use to divert additional water from the Mississippi River into the Morganza floodway, which merges downstream with the Atchafalaya floodway before entering the Gulf. Diversion of water from the Mississippi's main channel has the effect of lowering water level in the Mississippi downstream of the spillway, helping to relieve stress on levees and other flood control structures both upstream and down. Besides controlling flooding in a given event, the system is also designed to prevent the Mississippi River from permanently altering course down the Atchafalaya River, bypassing Baton Rouge and New Orleans.<ref name='USACE' /><ref name=\"AmericasWetlands\" /><ref name='Weeks' /><ref name=\"InteractiveMap\" />\n\nWater that passes the Morganza Spillway first enters the Morganza Floodway, which extends from the spillway at the Mississippi River south to the East Atchafalaya River levee. The floodway, {{convert|20|mi}} long and {{convert|5|mi}} wide, includes a stilling basin, an approach channel, an outlet channel, and two guide [[levee]]s.<ref name='USACE' /> From there, diverted water enters the [[Atchafalaya River Basin]] Floodway near [[Krotz Springs, Louisiana]],<ref name='USACE' /> and continues to the Gulf of Mexico.\n\nIn an extreme flood event, a major release of water from the Morganza Spillway into the Morganza Floodway and Atchafalaya Basin inundates not only the floodways themselves (between their levees), but extensive additional areas of southern Louisiana throughout the [[Atchafalaya Basin]]. In such an event, the water level of the Mississippi, high enough to overtop the Spillway, would already be flooding some areas in the Basin downstream of the spillway, due to increased flow through the ORCS and the ORCAS, as well as possible overtopping of levees near the spillway.<ref name=\"2008leveetopped\" /> This flooding, plus any additional water from a Morganza Spillway release, together determine the total extent of flooding throughout the Atchafalaya Basin during a major Mississippi River flood.\n\nAt risk in the Atchafalaya Basin are [[Morgan City, Louisiana|Morgan City]] (population 13,500), various smaller populated places, many farms, thousands of oil and gas wells, and considerable swampland. Inhabitants know that the region is a natural [[floodplain]], and the Corps of Engineers issues written notices annually to all interests reminding them of the possibility that it might open the spillway and flood the area.  Any decision to open the spillway must be carefully planned to give ample warning and protect life and property.   Part of that planning process includes the Corps' preparation of maps known as \"inundation scenarios\" so that interested parties can discuss how much water, if any, should be allowed through the spillway.<ref name='USACE' /><ref name=TP1>{{cite web|last=Schliefstein|first=Mark|title=Record high river likely to require opening of Morganza Spillway next week (May 4, 2011, revised May 9, 2011)|url=http://www.nola.com/weather/index.ssf/2011/05/record_high_river_likely_to_re.html|publisher=The Times-Picayune (New Orleans)|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=TP2>{{cite web|last=Schliefstein|first=Mark|title=Morganza Spillway might be opened to ease swollen Mississippi River (May 8, 2011, revised May 9, 2011)|url=http://www.nola.com/weather/index.ssf/2011/05/morganza_spillway_might_be_ope.html|publisher=The Times-Picayune (New Orleans)|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.thenewsstar.com/article/20110510/NEWS01/105100316 Morganza Spillway expected to open soon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514001342/http://www.thenewsstar.com/article/20110510/NEWS01/105100316 |date=2011-05-14 }}, ''The News Star'': May 9, 2011, Mike Hasten</ref><ref>[http://www.batonrougetoday.com/2011/05/06/gov-jindal-asks-army-corps-to-release-map-outlining-impact-of-possible-opening-of-morganza-spillway-says-state-continues-to-prepare-for-flooding/ Gov. Jindal Asks Army Corps to Release Map Outlining Impact of Possible Opening of Morganza Spillway, Says State Continues to Prepare for Flooding], ''Baton Rouge Today'': May 6, 2011. {{Dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=Trading>{{cite news|author1=Vastag, Brian |author2=Lisa Rein |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Trading one deluge for another? As panic rises with the Mississippi, engineers consider flooding farms to protect two La. cities|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=May 12, 2011| page=Pages A1 & A6}}</ref><ref name=Bloomberg>{{cite web|author1=Sullivan, Brian K. |author2=Leela Landress |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Morganza Spillway to open as river flow rises to threshold|url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-05-14/morganza-spillway-to-open-as-river-flow-rises-to-threshold.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110804183328/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-05-14/morganza-spillway-to-open-as-river-flow-rises-to-threshold.html|archivedate=2011-08-04|publisher=Bloomberg Businessweek|accessdate=15 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Daniels|first=Ronald Joel|title=On Risk and Disaster: Lessons from Hurricane Katrina|year=2006|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|page=44}}</ref><ref name='CorpsInundMap'>{{cite web|title=Corps Releases Inundation Map|url=http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/news/view.asp?ID=461|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110729011745/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/news/view.asp?ID=461|archivedate=2011-07-29|date = 7 May 2011|work=News Release|publisher=U.S. Army Corps of Engineers|accessdate=10 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring both moderate and severe floods of the Mississippi, the [[Bonnet Carr\u00e9 Spillway]] can also be opened to help protect New Orleans, many parts of which are below sea level. The Bonnet Carr\u00e9 Spillway, built after the [[Great Mississippi Flood of 1927]], is located well downstream of Morganza, where the Mississippi River approaches [[Lake Pontchartrain]] near New Orleans. The Corps uses Bonnet Carr\u00e9 to divert floodwaters into the lake in order to protect the levees near New Orleans.\n\nIntegrity of the Morganza Spillway, the Old River Control Structure, and nearby levees is essential to prevent the Mississippi from diverting its main channel into the Atchafalaya Basin.<ref>see [[2011 Mississippi River floods#Risk of major course change in the Lower Mississippi River|\"Risk of major course change in the Lower Mississippi River\"]] for further discussion</ref>\n\n== Flood events and the Morganza Spillway ==\nSince its completion in 1954, the Morganza Spillway has been opened twice, in 1973 and 2011. The Morganza Spillway was also considered for opening during other major floods of the Lower Mississippi River.\n\n===First opening of gates (1973)===\nOn April 17, 1973, in order to lower the water level of the Mississippi River and relieve pressure on the Old River Control Structure, the Corps of Engineers opened 42 of the 125 steel gates of the Morganza Spillway for the first time since its completion, allowing about half of its maximum designed flowrate to pass from the Mississippi into the Atchafalaya Basin. The spillway received minor scouring and slight damage to the stilling basin, and substantial flooding occurred in the Atchafalaya Basin. After the 1973 flood, the structure was restored to its original condition.<ref name='USACE' /><ref name='Weeks' /><ref name=\"Engineers\">{{cite news|title=Engineers Open Steel Gate of Morganza Spillway|page=93|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|date=April 18, 1973}}</ref><ref name=\"Community\">{{cite news|title=Community effort helps farmers. Levee built to protect land from flooding.|author=Amy Wold|newspaper=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)]]|page=B1|date=March 27, 2008|accessdate=May 15, 2011|url=http://www.2theadvocate.com/news/17041411.html?c=1290013583745}}{{Dead link|date=December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Gates left closed in floods of 1983, 1993, 1997, 2008, and 2016===\nThe issue of opening the gates to keep the Mississippi in its current place was next raised in May 1983.<ref>{{cite news|title=Along The Levee, The River Is Rising|author=Julia Cass|newspaper=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]|page=A1|date=May 27, 1983}}</ref> Although the gates were not opened, [[Louisiana Highway 1]] running across the spillway was closed, and the Corps of Engineers built a {{convert|12|ft|m|adj=on}} ring dike and put a blanket of earth across a section of the spillway to contain water pouring underneath it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cold Grips Midwest As More Floods Swamp Texas, Salt Lake City|author=United Press International|newspaper=[[Miami Herald]]|page=A4|date=June 7, 1983}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Great Mississippi and Missouri Rivers Flood of 1993|Great Mississippi and Missouri Rivers Flood in 1993]], officials decided to leave the gates of the Morganza Floodway closed.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Flood Of 1993|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|page=B6|date=July 10, 1993}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1997, the river water flow at [[Baton Rouge]] reached {{convert|10600000|gal|cuft|abbr=on}} ({{convert|10600000|gal|m3|disp=output only}}) per second.<ref name=\"Shipping\">{{cite news|title=Shipping Perilous, B.R. Levees Threatened|author=Chris Gray|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|page=A1|date=March 21, 1997}}</ref> However, the flow rate never reached the threshold of {{convert|11200000|gal|cuft|abbr=on}} ({{convert|11200000|gal|m3|disp=output only}}) per second for opening Morganza,<ref name=\"Shipping\"/> and residents of [[Sicily Island, Louisiana]], became angry that the spillway was not opened to prevent flooding in their homes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Home Not Flooded? Stay Out Of Shelter|author=Leslie Zganjar|newspaper=[[Seattle Times]]|page=A8|date=March 21, 1997|accessdate=May 15, 2011|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19970321&slug=2529854}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Using Morganza Endangers Business, Homes, Wildlife|author=Mark Schleifstein And Joan Treadway|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|page=A1|date=March 22, 1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=River Still Making Trouble Corps Snares Spillway Boater|author=Rhonda Bell|newspaper=[[The Times-Picayune]]|page=A1|date=March 23, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn March\u2013April 2008, officials considered but declined to open the spillway gates.<ref name=\"Community\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Gov. Jindal Holds Press Conference To Give Update On Rising Waters & Parishes In State Of Emergency With GOHSEP, Officials|author=Melissa Sellers|newspaper=US State News|date=April 6, 2008|accessdate=May 15, 2011|url=http://gohsep.la.gov/archive/2008/jindalriswaterrelease040608.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916093845/http://gohsep.la.gov/archive/2008/jindalriswaterrelease040608.htm|archivedate=2011-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=State, federal officials bracing for continued high water|author=M. Hasten|newspaper=[[The Times (Shreveport)]]|page=B05|date=April 7, 2008}}</ref>  While the spillway gates remained closed then, flooding occurred in the Morganza forebay when the Mississippi River crested higher than the potato ridge levee at the forebay entrance. Local residents and [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] troops attempted to add height to the permanent levee by building a supplemental [[sandbag]] levee on top of it. However, additional rainfall raised the flood crest higher than even the supplemental sandbags, sending floodwaters over these levees into {{convert|3000|acres}} of cropland located within the floodway.<ref name=\"2008leveetopped\">[http://midsouthfarmer.com/story.aspx/water/over/the/levee/in/louisiana/14/16637 Water Over the Levee in Louisiana: 3,000 acres of wheat acres hurt] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110821231242/http://midsouthfarmer.com/story.aspx/water/over/the/levee/in/louisiana/14/16637 |date=2011-08-21 }}, ''Midsouth Farmer'', April 8, 2008.</ref>\nIn the spring of 2016, the Corps considered opening the spillway but the forecast was lowered for the crest of the Mississippi River at Red River Landing, so the gates were left closed.\n\n=== Second opening of gates (2011) ===\n{{main|2011 Mississippi River floods}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; clear:right;margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;\"\n|+Flooding Scenarios<ref name='USACE NOD'>{{cite web | url = http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/missriver.asp | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081009210808/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/missriver.asp | archivedate = 2008-10-09 | title = The Mississippi River | accessdate = 2011-05-12 | date = 2011-05-09 | publisher = United States Army Corps of Engineers}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:NO District Inundation Spring May 2011.jpg|thumb|200px|Anticipated inundation from Scenario&nbsp;1]]\n|-\n|[[File:NODInundationMay2011Scenario1a.jpg|thumb|200px|Anticipated inundation from Scenario&nbsp;1a]]\n|-\n|[[File:NODInundationMay2011Scenario2.jpg|thumb|200px|Anticipated inundation from Scenario&nbsp;2]]\n|-\n|[[File:NODInundationMay2011Scenario3.jpg|thumb|200px|Anticipated inundation from Scenario&nbsp;3]]\n|}\nThe 2011 Mississippi River floods began to become serious in April. In response, the Corps first analyzed the flooding, and then opened the spillway in a controlled manner. The Corps studied four flooding scenarios, all of which assumed the Bonnet Carr\u00e9 Spillway would be concurrently operating at full capacity (100%).\n*Scenario 1: Open the Morganza Spillway to half (50%) of its maximum capacity, which would divert {{convert|300000|cuft/s}} of water.\n*Scenario 1a: Open the Morganza Spillway to one-quarter (25%) of its maximum capacity, which would divert {{convert|150000|cuft/s}} of water.\n*Scenario 2: Do not open the Morganza Spillway, and keep the Old River Control Structure (ORCS) at its routine operating level of only 30% of the Mississippi's flow;  no additional water would be diverted\n*Scenario 3: Do not open the Morganza Spillway, and open the ORCS somewhat more, which would divert an extra {{convert|150000|cuft/s}} of water.\n\nFollowing this analysis, which showed that extensive flooding was expected in the Atchafalaya Basin regardless of the choice made regarding the Morganza Spillway, the Corps decided to start the 2011 diversion by opening the spillway a bit less than described in scenario 1a (21%, not 25%)<ref name=\"NOLAFirstGate\">[http://www.nola.com/environment/index.ssf/2011/05/morganza_floodway_opens_to_div.html Morganza Floodway opens to divert Mississippi River away from Baton Rouge, New Orleans | NOLA.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nThe [[Governor]] of Louisiana, [[Bobby Jindal]], had meanwhile sent a letter on May 4, 2011, to [[Robert Gates]], the [[United States Secretary of Defense]], requesting that the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] be deployed under [[Title 32 of the United States Code]] status to respond to record water levels in Louisiana, where there was \"a significant probability that the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers [would] open the Morganza Spillway for the first time since 1973.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Governor Jindal Sends Letter To Dept. Of Defense Requesting National Guard|newspaper=States News Service (released by the office of the governor of Louisiana)|date=May 4, 2011|accessdate=May 15, 2011|url=http://www.katc.com/news/governor-jindal-sends-letter-to-dept-of-defense-requesting-national-guard/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314030603/http://www.katc.com/news/governor-jindal-sends-letter-to-dept-of-defense-requesting-national-guard/|archivedate=2012-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThe second opening of the Morganza Spillway began with the lifting of a single floodgate on May 14, 2011. Diversion of {{convert|125000|cuft/s}} of water from the Mississippi River to the Atchafalaya Basin was planned during this event, with the structure operating at about 21% of its capacity.  This diversion was deemed necessary to protect levees and prevent major flooding in Baton Rouge and New Orleans, with the tradeoff of creating possibly severe flooding in the Atchafalaya Basin.<ref name='USACE' /><ref>[http://thewatchers.adorraeli.com/2011/05/14/morganza-spillway-about-to-open/ The Watchers - US 2011 Great Flood: Morganza spillway about to open<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nBy May 18, 2011, a total of 17 gates (the largest number for the 2011 event) had been opened by the Corps of Engineers. The Corps estimated the flow rate at {{convert|114000|cuft/s|abbr=on}}. However, on May 25, new estimates from the [[U.S. Geologic Survey]] (USGS) described a much higher rate of {{convert|172000|cuft/s|abbr=on}}, resulting in the closure of 3 bays by May 26, and additional closures by May 29, bringing the total to 11 bays with an estimated diversion rate of {{convert|120000|cuft/s|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"close-bays-whoops\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/news/view.asp?ID=482 | title=Corps begins to close bays on Morganza Floodway | publisher=US Army Corps of Engineers, Team New Orleans | date=May 26, 2011 | accessdate=May 29, 2011 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812074410/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/news/view.asp?ID=482 | archivedate=August 12, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"USACoE-pace\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/morganza.asp | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514001802/http://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/bcarre/morganza.asp | archivedate=2011-05-14 | title=Morganza Floodway Opening Pace: 2011 | publisher=US Army Corps of Engineers, Team New Orleans | date=May 29, 2011 | accessdate=May 29, 2011}}</ref> The Corps continued to evaluate the flow and close additional bays as appropriate. By June 6, the number of open gates had been reduced to seven,<ref>[http://www.wafb.com/story/14846370/only-7-bays-remain-open-at-morganza-spillway WAFB: Only 7 Bays Remain Open at Morganze Spillway]</ref> and by June 8, only two gates were still open.<ref name=\"USACoE-pace\" /> All bays were closed on July 7, 2011.\n\nThe Corps had estimated that it would take opening one-fourth of the spillway\u2019s 125 bays \u2014 or 31 bays \u2014 to control the flow of the river through Baton Rouge in response to a forecast crest of {{convert|45|ft|m}} anticipated on Tuesday, May 17, 2011, which must remain below {{convert|1500000|cuft/s|abbr=on}} of water per second through Baton Rouge to ensure the integrity of the levee system.<ref>{{cite news|last=KENNEDY|first=KATIE|title=Planning for high water|url=http://www.2theadvocate.com/news/Planning-for-high-water.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518231217/http://www.2theadvocate.com/news/Planning-for-high-water.html|archivedate=2011-05-18|accessdate=15 May 2011|newspaper=The Advocate|date=15 May 2011}}</ref> Since Morganza never operated above {{convert|172000|cuft/s|abbr=on}}, the flooding in the Atchafalaya Basin was considerably lower than had been anticipated during the initial estimates of {{convert|300000|cuft/s|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"close-bays-whoops\" /> By May 29, the Corps had also opened 330 of the 350 bays of the [[Bonnet Carr\u00e9 Spillway]] located near New Orleans.<ref name=\"USACoE-pace\" />\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Morganza Floodway opened in Louisiana seen from Air.jpg|<small>Aerial photograph of the first bay opening on the Morganza Floodway on 14 May 2011. The Mississippi River is in the upper left background, and the Atchafalaya Floodway to the right.</small>\nImage:Morganza Floodway Travel Times May 2011.jpg|Water travel time down the Morganza Floodway after the May 14, 2011 opening.\nImage:May 2011 Morganza Spillway Opens in Louisiana.jpg|Natural-colour satellite image of the Floodway on May 15, 2011.\nImage:May 2011 Morganza Spillway Opens in Louisiana (False Colour).jpg|False colour satellite image of the Floodway on May 15, 2011.\n</gallery>\n\n=== Third Opening of Gates (2019) CANCELLED! ===\n\n''Main article: [[Mississippi River Floods of 2019]]''\n\nOn Wednesday May 22, 2019, the U.S. Army Corps Of Engineers announced due to the extended flood event on the Mississippi River, which had been above flood stage since January 2019, that they were anticipating the third opening of the Morganza Spillway. An anticipated further river rise stoked fears that the Mississippi River waters would overtop the spillway, which would destroy the structure. The possible opening could happen as early as June 2, 2019. On Monday May 27, 2019, the Army Corps of Engineers officially announced it will open Morganza on Sunday, June 2, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/Media/News-Releases/Article/1858495/usace-to-operate-morganza-control-structure/|title=USACE to operate Morganza Control Structure|website=New Orleans District|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThe US Army Corps of Engineers New Orleans issued a press release on May 30, 2019, announcing the postponement of the opening of the Morganza Spillway until June 6, 2019.The spillway was never opened in 2019. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/Media/News-Releases/Article/1861810/update-operation-of-the-morganza-floodway-postponed/fbclid/IwAR20FuFYBdvtB5k82OL9o_4rCSGeBx6xsOO4Tqgug9MNzqd2MS2nYGJCS6U/fbclid/IwAR0P1dRoUIArOU1ssjsVCLyr3Unh7rMZ_Vu9eJwKTEsdW2g1j9Yfcrz5Vx4/|title=UPDATE: OPERATION OF THE MORGANZA FLOODWAY POSTPONED|website=New Orleans District|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref>  The opening was later postponed again to June 9, then indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/Media/News-Releases/Article/1864707/update-operation-of-the-morganza-floodway-postponed/|title=UPDATE: OPERATION OF THE MORGANZA FLOODWAY POSTPONED|website=New Orleans District|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mvn.usace.army.mil/Media/News-Releases/Article/1868632/update-operation-of-the-morganza-floodway-postponed/|title=UPDATE: OPERATION OF THE MORGANZA FLOODWAY POSTPONED|website=New Orleans District|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[West Atchafalaya Floodway]]\n*The \"Atchafalaya\" section of the book ''[[The Control of Nature]]'' by [[John McPhee]].  {{ISBN|0-374-12890-1}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=7366074n Army Engineers Open Morganza Spillway]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Khjkpkz7iOU Morganza Spillway Fish Jumping through Gates]\n*For other images of the Morganza Control Structure in operation during the 2011 flood, see the [https://www.flickr.com/photos/37671998@N05/sets/72157626602502997/ U.S. Army Corps of Engineers Flickr page].\n\n{{coord|30.7766|-91.6199|region:US-LA_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Pointe Coupee Parish, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:United States Army Corps of Engineers]]\n", "name_user": "Chessrat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThird Opening of Gates (2019) CANCELLED!:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morganza_Spillway"}
{"title_page": "Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez", "text_new": "{{short description|Interim President of Bolivia since 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{spanish name|[[\u00c1\u00f1ez]]|[[Ch\u00e1vez (surname)|Ch\u00e1vez]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez\n| image               = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez.jpg\n| caption             = \u00c1\u00f1ez in 2016\n| order = 66th \n| office              = President of Bolivia\n| term_start          = 12 November 2019\n| term_end            = \n| vicepresident       = <!-- ''None'' -->\n| predecessor         = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[President pro tempore of the Community of Latin American and Caribbean States|President pro tempore of CELAC]]\n| term_start1         = 12 November 2019\n| term_end1           = 8 January 2020{{Efn|CELAC ''pro tempore'' presidency is assigned to countries and it automatically passes to the next president after elections. After the [[2019 Bolivian political crisis]], Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez would become ''pro tempore'' president of CELAC. However, Mexico called for a new CELAC summit on its own. Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez denounced that the summit should be called for by Bolivia. As the result of this dispute, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez did not attend to the CELAC summit and did not formally pass the ''pro tempore'' presidency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elimparcial.com/mundo/Bolivia-no-asistira-al-cambio-de-presidencia-de-la-Celac-por-roces-con-Mexico-20191223-0073.html|title=Bolivia no asistir\u00e1 al cambio de presidencia de la Celac por roces con M\u00e9xico|work=El Imparcial|date=23 December 2019|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/es/mundo/bolivia-rechaza-que-m%C3%A9xico-convocara-a-reuni%C3%B3n-de-la-celac-sin-consultarle-previamente/1682226|title=Bolivia rechaza que M\u00e9xico convocara a reuni\u00f3n de la Celac sin consultarle previamente|work=Anadolu Agency|first=Sant\u0131ago|last=Serna Duque|date=24 December 2020|access-date=11 April 2020|language=es}}</ref>}}\n| predecessor1        = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor1          = [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]]\n| office2             = [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly|Senator]] for [[Beni Department|Beni]]\n| term_start2         = 22 January 2010\n| term_end2           = 12 November 2019\n| office3             = [[Bolivian Constituent Assembly of 2006\u201307|Member of the Constituent Assembly]]\n| term_start3         = 6 August 2006\n| term_end3           = 6 August 2007\n| birth_name          = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1967|8|13}}\n| birth_place         = [[Trinidad, Bolivia|Trinidad]], [[Beni Department|Beni]], Bolivia\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| spouse              = H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal\n| party               = [[Democrat Social Movement]] [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]]\n| signature           = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez'''<ref>{{citation |title=Entrevista Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v185AWdeDE0 |language=en |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> ({{IPA-es|\u025f\u029da\u02c8nine \u02c8a\u0272es}}; born 13 August 1967)<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date=16 October 2015 |website=C\u00e1mara de Senadores |language=es |accessdate=11 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111145518/https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |archivedate=11 November 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is a Bolivian politician and lawyer currently serving as the Interim [[President of Bolivia]] since November 2019, after the [[Evo Morales government resignation|resignation of the government of Evo Morales]]. Her interim term will end when [[2020 Bolivian general election|new elections]] take place on an as yet undetermined date in 2020.\n\nShe was previously an opposition [[Senate of Bolivia|senator]] from the northeastern [[Departments of Bolivia|department]] of [[Beni, Bolivia|Beni]], belonging to the center-right [[Democrat Social Movement]]. Her political position has been described by journalists as [[right-wing]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization |first=Dan |last=Collyns |date=14 November 2019 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/jeanine-anez-declares-bolivia-interim-president-191112233635201.html |title=Jeanine Anez declares herself Bolivia interim president |date=12 November 2019 |website=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> and anti-[[Evo Morales|Morales]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cronista.com/internacionales/Bolivia-quien-es-Jeanine-Anez-Chavez-la-mujer-que-puede-quedar-al-mando-de-la-transicion-20191110-0019.html |title=Bolivia: qui\u00e9n es Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, la mujer que puede quedar al mando de la transici\u00f3n |date=11 November 2019 |website=El Cronista |trans-title=Bolivia: who is Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, the woman who can be in charge of the transition |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html |title=After Morales' resignation, a question for Bolivia: Was this the democratic will, or a coup? |last=Faiola |first=Anthony |date= |website=[[The Washington Post]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111194058/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html|archive-date=2019-11-11|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50399640 |title=Bolivian senator assumes interim presidency |last= |first= |date=13 November 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez has a graduate degree in law and legal sciences from the Autonomous University of the Beni Jos\u00e9 Ballivi\u00e1n.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Career==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez passed the bar in 1991.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was formerly a media presenter<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/mundo/perfil-de-jeanine-anez-nueva-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-432904 |title=\u00bfQui\u00e9n es Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la nueva presidenta interina de Bolivia? |first=Casa Editorial El |last=Tiempo |date=13 November 2019 |location=Colombia |language=es |website=[[ElTiempo.com]]}}</ref> and director at Totalvision.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Constituent Assembly (2006\u20132008)===\nBetween 2006 and 2008, she served as a constituent assemblywoman for the drafting of the new constitutional charter. She was a member of the Constituent Assembly for the commission of organization and structure of the country, also working as part of the Judiciary.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Senate (2010\u20132019)===\nIn 2010, she was elected to the [[Bolivian Senate|Senate]] as a member of the party [[Plan Progress for Bolivia \u2013 National Convergence|Plan Progress for Bolivia-National Convergence]] (P.P.B - C.N), representing the Department of Beni in the National Assembly.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date= |access-date=21 April 2014 |publisher=vicepresidencia.gob.bo |language=es |format= |quote= }}</ref> She ran for governor of Beni in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Jeanine-Anez-precandidata-gobernacion-Beni_0_1697830274.html |title=La senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez surge como primera precandidata opositora a la gobernaci\u00f3n de Beni; el MSM apunta a una tercera opci\u00f3n |last=Corz |first=Carlos |date=1 October 2012 |website=La Raz\u00f3n |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy 2019, she was the second vice president of the Senate, and her alternate was Franklin Valdivia Leigue.<ref name=\":0\" /> This role placed her fifth in the [[President of Bolivia#Current line of succession|line of succession to the presidency]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Before the presidential elections in 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez had questioned the reliability of opinion polls, based on unclear methods and inconsistent results.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/8/19/piden-informe-escrito-al-tse-por-la-encuestadora-viaciencia-228016.html |title=Piden informe escrito al TSE por la encuestadora ViaCiencia |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"Interim president of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)\"></span>Interim President of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)===\n\nOn 10 November, Morales and his vice president, [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]], [[Evo Morales government resignation|resigned from office]] after pressure from political opponents and civic groups and losing support from former political allies, the police and the [[Armed Forces of Bolivia|military]];<ref name=\"Londo\u00f1o\">Ernesto Londo\u00f1o, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/evo-morales-bolivia.html Bolivian Leader Evo Morales Steps Down], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (10 November 2019).</ref>. This was followed by the resignation of [[Adriana Salvatierra Arriaza]], the president of the [[Bolivian Senate]], who was next in the constitutional line of succession<ref name=\"GuerreroAndone\">Kay Guerrero & Dakin Andone, [https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/10/americas/bolivia-new-election-audit/index.html Bolivian President Evo Morales steps down following accusations of election fraud], CNN (10 November 2019).</ref>\u2014leading to a situation where all constitutional successors were exhausted. The role of acting President of the Senate would normally fall to the vice-president of the Senate, Rub\u00e9n Medinaceli, but since he also had resigned, the position fell to A\u00f1ez as second vice-president of the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/76278_salvatierra-asume-pide-que-haya-mas-inclusion-de-mujeres-y-jovenes|title=Salvatierra sworn in; Calls for more inclusion of women and young people|website=El Deber|date=18 January 2019|language=es|author=Jes\u00fas Alanoca Paco}}</ref> Thus A\u00f1ez became the highest-ranking official in the line of succession to the presidency of Bolivia and stated an acceptance to fill the role if needed. The succession was not automatic, however, as the Legislative Assembly would need to hold emergency meetings to accept the abdications of the President and Vice-President and determine who was next in line due to the lack of constitutional guidance.<ref name=\"vicepresidente1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-50370125 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez en proceso de ratificaci\u00f3n tras renuncia del Presidente, Vicepresidente, Presidente del Senado y Presidente de la C\u00e1mara de Diputados de Bolivia |editor=BBC News Mundo |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez could not attend an emergency assembly until the day after Morales' resignation, as she was in Beni and there were no Sunday flights from there to the capital of [[La Paz]].<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nOn 11 November, A\u00f1ez arrived at [[El Alto International Airport|La Paz-El Alto airport]] and was taken in a military helicopter to a nearby Air Force base. From there, she traveled to the Bolivian Senate. At 4pm, an emergency vote took place to formally accept the resignations of the previous day. <ref name=\"Huff-Post\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.fr/entry/apres-la-demission-devo-morales-les-insoumis-denoncent-un-coup-detat_fr_5dc91fa7e4b00927b236112e |title=Apr\u00e8s la d\u00e9mission d'Evo Morales, les insoumis d\u00e9noncent un \"coup d'\u00c9tat\" |date=11 November 2019 |website=Le Huffington Post}}</ref> Morales' MAS party, which still held a majority in the upper chamber, boycotted this vote. Constitutional experts Paul Coca and Israel Alanoca stated that, while the normal quorum would have been desirable for purpose of quelling accusations of a coup d'etat, there was no specific regulation to deal with the resignation of leaders and an emergency vote on the grounds of human rights concerns and establishing social peace would be legally valid.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/11/si-no-hay-quorum-en-la-alp-se-puede-apelar-al-voto-de-urgencia-237110.html|title=If there is no quorum in the ALP, an emergency vote can be applied|language=es|date=11 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn the evening of 12 November, per article 169 of the [[Constitution of Bolivia]], \u00c1\u00f1ez was declared acting [[president of Bolivia]] in front of a session of the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156411_anez-asume-la-presidencia-de-bolivia-ante-vacancia-y-aplicando-la-sucesion-constitucional|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez asume la Presidencia de Bolivia ante vacancia y aplicando la sucesi\u00f3n constitucional|trans-title=\u00c1\u00f1ez assumes the Presidency of Bolivia due to vacancy and applying the constitutional succession|website=El Deber|language=es|access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> This vote was also boycotted by MAS, who dubbed the vote \"illegal\". <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/12/anez-asume-la-presidencia-para-pacificar-el-pais-237195.html|title=Anez assumes the presidency to pacify the country|language=es|date=12 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/12/evo-morales-arrives-mexico-bolivia-power-vacuum |title=Bolivia: Jeanine A\u00f1ez claims presidency after ousting of Evo Morales |location=La Paz |first1=Jo |last1=Tuckman |first2=Dan |last2=Collyns |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 }}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/13/americas/bolivia-political-unrest-intl-hnk/index.html |title=Bolivian senator declares herself acting president -- but she may be on shaky ground |first1=Joshua |last1=Berlinger |first2=Gustavo |last2=Vald\u00e9s |website=CNN |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez obtained the favorable vote of the remaining parties, a third part of the parliament. <ref>{{cite news |title=La senadora Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez se proclama presidenta de Bolivia sin qu\u00f3rum en el Parlamento |url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/12/america/1573566340_453048.html |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=13 November 2019 |accessdate=13 November 2019|issn=1134-6582|language=es|first=Francesco|last=Manetto}}</ref> The move was later upheld by the [[Plurinational Constitutional Court]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/156414_tcp-avala-sucesion-constitucional-en-la-presidencia|title=TCP avala sucesi\u00f3n constitucional en la Presidencia |trans-title=TCP uphelds constitutional succession in the Presidency |website=El Deber |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \n\nAfter taking office, the governments of [[Canada]], [[Brazil]], the [[European Union]], [[Russia]] and the [[United States]] recognized \u00c1\u00f1ez as the acting president of Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Canada will 'support' Bolivian opposition government |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/bolivia-canada-anez-government-1.5360138 |work=CBC News |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>{{when|date=December 2019}}<!-- the timing of this recognition should be included in the prose -->\n\nOn 13 November Salvatierra contended that her resignation was not valid since it had not been accepted by the Senate, and therefore, \u00c1\u00f1ez should not be able to assume the Presidency via becoming President of the Senate.<ref name=\"dispute\">{{cite news |title=Presidenta de Senado boliviano denuncia presi\u00f3n a dirigentes |url=https://www.telesurtv.net/news/bolivia-presidenta-senado-denuncia-presion-dirigentes-20191113-0021.html |accessdate=14 November 2019 |work=www.telesurtv.net |agency=teleSUR |date=13 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> This prompted a further session on the Senate on 14 November, this time with the involvement of MAS, that reaffirmed Salvatierra's resignation more formally and elected M\u00f3nica Eva Copa from the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] as the new president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol%C3%ADtica/eva-copa-es-la-nueva-presidenta-del-senado|language=es|title=Eva Copa is the new president of the Senate|date=15 November 2019|website=www.atb.com.bo}}</ref>\n\nAmid a pledge to \"rebuild democracy\", A\u00f1ez unveiled her new [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]]. Her senior ministers included prominent businesspeople from [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]]. The first eleven members of her cabinet did not include any members of the [[indigenous peoples in Bolivia]], which ''[[The Guardian]]'' described as a sign that she did \"not intend to reach across the country's deep political and ethnic divide\". Later appointments of the remaining positions would include two indigenous members. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Anez-completa-gabinete-ministra-Alto_0_3257674272.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez posesiona cinco nuevos ministros; Yujra besa la wiphala y va por di\u00e1logo con El Alto - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/ministros-posesion-bolivia-anez_0_3260074003.html|title=A\u00f1ez posesiona a Carlos Huallpa en Miner\u00eda y a Virginia Patty Torres en Educaci\u00f3n - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref> Morales' cabinet had also included two indigenous persons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/especial01/2017/1/22/gabinete-tuvo-rostros-indigenas-pero-pocos-ministros-poder-124588.html|title=Gabinete tuvo rostros ind\u00edgenas, pero pocos ministros con poder - Diario Pagina Siete|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref>\nHer designated interior minister vowed to \"hunt down\" his predecessor, which reportedly stroked fears of a \"[[witch-hunt]]\" against members of Morales' administration.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization |last=Collyns |first=Dan |date=14 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 November 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She further stated that Morales would not be permitted to run in an upcoming election for a fourth term, should he return to Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-bolivias-interim-leader-says-evo-morales-cant-run-in-new-election/ |title=Bolivia's interim leader says Evo Morales can't run in new election |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-interim-president-bars-morales-from-new-elections/a-51259511 |title=Bolivia: Interim president bars Morales from new elections {{!}} DW {{!}} 15 November 2019  |last=Welle (www.dw.com) |first=Deutsche |website=DW.COM |language=en-GB |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe new interim government of president Jeanine A\u00f1ez has denounced foreign influence in the country since taking power, naming Colombians, Peruvians, Cubans and Venezuelans at different times. Her government has blamed foreigners for provoking violent clashes during more than a month of post-election violence in [[Bolivia]] that has left dozens of people dead. Police arrested an Argentine national, 44-year-old Facundo Morales Schoenfeld, in the eastern province of Santa Cruz, who is a former member of the [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] (FARC) and was participating among the protesters in [[Yapacan\u00ed]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/americas/bolivia-unveils-anti-terror-unit-to-fight-threatening-foreign-groups |title=Bolivia unveils anti-terror unit to fight 'threatening' foreign groups |date=4 December 2019 |website=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 December, \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that she would not be a candidate or support any candidate in the upcoming presidential election.<ref>[https://rpp.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/bolivia-jeanine-anez-no-postulara-a-la-presidencia-segun-el-gobierno-interino-noticia-1233337 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez no postular\u00e1 a la Presidencia de Bolivia, seg\u00fan el Gobierno interino.] Publicado el 5 de diciembre de 2019. Consultado el 8 de diciembre de 2019.</ref> This was further reiterated on 15 January 2020 by Minister for the Presidency [[:w:es:Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez|Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], who said that \"[\u00c1\u00f1ez] will not be a candidate. The President has stated on several occasions, she will not be a candidate, this is a government of peace, transition, and management because you can not stop the state apparatus.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/jeanine-anez-presidencia-gobierno-elecciones-bolivia_0_3294870527.html| language=es|title=Government clarifies that Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez will not be a candidate for the Presidency}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January 2020, the government decided to ratify the 22 January public holiday created by Morales to celebrate the founding of the [[Plurinational State of Bolivia]] via the 2009 constitution. On this day, the President of Bolivia normally addresses the nation, but doubt had been expressed whether this holiday would go ahead due to its strong political connection with Morales and MAS. In a public statement, however, minister for the Presidency [[Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], said \"January 22 is a holiday by presidential decree, we are going to respect that decree and our president is evaluating if she is going to make a report about the pillars of this government, which are transition, pacification and management.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/1/7/gobierno-ratifica-feriado-del-22-de-enero-anez-evalua-informe-de-gestion-242710.html | title=Government ratifies 22 January holiday and A\u00f1ez considers management address|language=es}}</ref>\n\nDespite her previous statements, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced her candidacy on 24 January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol\u00edtica/jeanine-\u00e1\u00f1ez-confirma-candidatura-presidencial-para-las-elecciones-generales|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez confirma candidatura presidencial para las elecciones generales|date=24 January 2020|access-date=24 January 2020|website=ATBDigital|language=es-ES}}</ref> A survey reported in the Bolivian newspaper ''[[Los Tiempos]]'' indicated that, while 43% of respondents considered her to have done a \"good or very good\" job as interim president (compared to 27% bad or very bad), only 24% of respondents believed that she should stand as a candidate in the upcoming elections. In the same poll, 63% of respondents agreed with the statement that \"as interim president, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez should call elections and not take advantage of her power to become a presidential candidate.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20200126/encuesta-aprueban-gestion-anez-pero-rechazan-candidatura| title=Survey approves of \u00c1\u00f1ez's term as president, but rejects her candidacy.|language=es|date=26 January 2020}}</ref> Her running mate who was previously critical of her decision to stand as a presidential candidate is [[Samuel Doria Medina]], a former presidential candidate and leader of the center-right [[National Unity Front]] party.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/05/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman| title=Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|date= 7 March 2020}}</ref>. They are standing under the newly formed [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]] alliance. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Unidad-Nacional-Sole-Vicepresidencia-Juntos_0_3304469555.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez and Doria Medina seal alliance and become presidential running mates| language=es|date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince early March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez has implemented numerous controls concerning the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bolivia|coronavirus pandemic]] including closing all borders, prohibiting all international and interdepartmental flights, a strict nationwide curfew and restricting driving to those transporting foods and supplies and those carrying out essential services. This crisis has also resulted in the postponement of the upcoming [[2020 Bolivian general election]], the delay having been agreed upon by all parties involved.\n\n== Political views ==\nA\u00f1ez is described as a [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-idUSKBN1XM1NV |title=Bolivian Senate head assumes interim presidency; Morales' loyalists object |date=13 November 2019 |work=Reuters |access-date=15 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-bolivian-senator-declares-herself-president-morales-denounces-coup |title=Bolivian senator declares herself interim president, Morales slams 'coup' |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> [[Religious conservatism|religious conservative]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/bolivia-s-new-leader-religious-conservative-jeanine-ez-chavez-faces-n1082426 |title=Bolivia's new leader, religious conservative Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez, faces daunting challenges |website=NBC News |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/14/bolivia-interim-leader-recognises-guaido-legitimate-venezuelan/ |title=Bolivia interim leader recognises Guaido as legitimate Venezuelan leader as balance shifts |last=Staff |first=Our Foreign |date=14 November 2019 |work=The Telegraph |access-date=15 November 2019 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and has been a critic of Evo Morales.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-senator-jeanine-anez-declares-herself-interim-president/a-51218963 |title=Bolivia: Senator Jeanine Anez declares herself interim president {{!}} DW {{!}} 12 November 2019 |last= |first= |date= |website=Deutsche Welle |language=en-GB |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Drugs===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez has spoken out against the proliferation of drug trafficking in South America.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2017/10/20/narcotrafico-anez-llama-canalla-romero-dice-sobrino-responsable-actos-156480.html |title=Narcotr\u00e1fico: A\u00f1ez llama \"canalla\" a Romero y dice que su sobrino es responsable de sus actos |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, her nephew was arrested in Brazil for smuggling 480 kilos of drugs. The security minister [[Carlos Romero (Bolivian politician)|Carlos Romero]] criticized \u00c1\u00f1ez and said that her position in the senate was \"rogue\" because of the relationship; \u00c1\u00f1ez responded by saying that she is not responsible for her nephew's actions, and criticized Romero because of his position in the government by saying that he is \"responsible for the growth of drug trafficking\". It was later revealed that another Bolivian arrested with drugs at the same time was the nephew of another politician, this time belonging to the MAS ruling party.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===Prison services===\nIn early 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez called for an investigation into prison wardens in Beni after speaking to victims of rape and abuse on the part of guards. She aimed to set a precedent to bring in new legislation that can be upheld.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/03/senadora-jeanine-anez-pide-al-gobierno-investigar-todas-carceletas-del-beni/ |title=Senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez pide al Gobierno investigar todas carceletas del Beni |website=eju.tv |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nShe describes herself as a [[Christianity|Christian]] and held up a large Bible while declaring herself the interim president; this was described by ''The Guardian'' as an \"explicit rebuke\" of Morales, who has a strained [[Evo Morales and the Roman Catholic Church|history with the Catholic Church]] and has expressed support for indigenous religious traditions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-jeanine-anez-stand-in-president-vowing-to-pacify-bolivia |title=Jeanine Anez: stand-in president vowing to 'pacify' Bolivia |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/13/jeanine-anez-bolivia-president-promises-new-elections |title=Bolivia's interim president Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez promises new elections |last=Collyns |first=Dan |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Under Morales, a new [[Constitution of Bolivia|Constitution]] was [[2009 Bolivian constitutional referendum|approved by referendum]] that gave Christianity equal status to other religions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-11/bolivia-faces-power-vacuum-and-more-chaos-after-morales-quits |title=Senator Brandishing Giant Bible Takes Over Bolivia Presidency |date=11 November 2019 |website=Bloomberg |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> A 2018 survey found that 70% of Bolivians identified as Catholic and 17.2% as Protestant of some form. 9.3% were non-religious.<ref>https://www.statista.com/statistics/1066911/religious-affiliation-in-bolivia/</ref> Political analyst Carlos Cordero states that \u201cShe is a believer, but she does not use her religiosity politically, she expresses it, she lives it.\u201d<ref>https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/30/las-quince-diferencias-en-el-estilo-de-gobernar-de-jeanine-anez-morales-241950.html</ref>\n\n===Venezuela===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez recognized [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] as acting president of Venezuela in the [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis]], 24 hours after taking office.<ref name=\"Alberto\">{{cite web |url=https://albertonews.com/principales/ultima-hora-bolivia-reconoce-a-juan-guaido-como-presidente-e-de-venezuela/ |title=Bolivia reconoce a Juan Guaid\u00f3 como presidente (E) de Venezuela |date=13 November 2019 |website=Albertonews.com |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> Her interim government also severed diplomatic relations with Venezuela's Maduro government, giving its diplomats 72 hours to leave the country.<ref name=\"lapiensa\">{{cite web |url=https://latinoamericapiensa.com/la-politica-internacional-de-anez-anuncio-la-salida-de-bolivia-del-alba-de-la-unasur-y-rompio-relaciones-con-venezuela/21065/ |title=La pol\u00edtica internacional de A\u00f1ez: anunci\u00f3 la salida de Bolivia del Alba, de la Unasur y rompi\u00f3 relaciones con Venezuela |language=es |website=Latinomerica Piensa |date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-bolivia-election-venezuela/bolivas-interim-government-to-ask-venezuelan-diplomats-to-leave-the-country-idUKKBN1XP23U |title=Boliva's interim government to ask Venezuelan diplomats to leave the country |website=Reuters |date=15 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez has also called on Guaid\u00f3 to appoint the new Venezuelan Ambassador to Bolivia, \"who will be recognized immediately by our government.\"<ref name=\"Alberto\"/>\n\nA month later, her government announced Bolivia's entry into the [[Lima Group]], a regional bloc established in 2017 with the purpose of finding a way out of the [[Crisis in Venezuela|Venezuelan crisis]]. The Bolivian foreign ministry said in a statement that it hoped to \u201ccontribute to a peaceful, democratic and constitutional solution to the crisis in Venezuela, which must be guided by the Venezuelan people.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | last1=Sigal | first1=Lucila | title=Bolivia announces entry into Lima Group to resolve Venezuelan crisis | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivia-announces-entry-into-lima-group-to-resolve-venezuelan-crisis-idUSKBN1YQ0JM | date=22 December 2019 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> On the same month, the interim government announced that they would give refuge to 200 Venezuelans \"who have fled their country for reasons of political order, of political persecution promoted by the [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] government.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/es/bolivia-dar%C3%A1-refugio-a-200-venezolanos-que-huyeron-por-persecuci%C3%B3n-pol%C3%ADtica/a-51665845|title=Bolivia will shelter 200 Venezuelans who fled for \"political persecution\"|last=|first=|date=13 December 2019|work=[[Deutsch Welle]]|access-date=4 January 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n===Violence against women and children===\nOn 6 February 2020, she invited the people of Bolivia to attend a march in Santa Cruz in support of the fight against violence against women and children, an issue increasingly highlighted by the Bolivian press. <ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/rascacielos/2020/3/8/feminicidios-en-bolivia-suenos-robados-248613.html|language=es|date=8 March 2020|title=Feminicides in Bolivia: Stolen Dreams}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/6/anez-pide-denunciar-la-violencia-contra-mujeres-ninos-en-una-marcha-245817.html|date=6 February 2020| title=A\u00f1ez asks to denounce violence against women and children in a march|language=es}}</ref>\n\nOn [[International Women's Day]], 8 March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced a $100 million investment in the fight against violence against women, She declared 2020 as the  Year of the Fight Against Feminicide and Infanticide in Bolivia, saying \"I am the worst news for all those murderers of women, users of violence, abusers, stalkers and rapists, because I will not get tired of closing against these aggressors\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.la-razon.com/sociedad/mujer-bolivia-anez-presidenta-violencia-genero_0_3326667313.html| title=\u00c1\u00f1ez: 'I will give everything to end gender violence'|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/3/10/violencia-anez-lanza-plan-con-una-inversion-de-us-100-millones-249125.html|title=Violence: A\u00f1ez launches plan with an investment of $ us 100 million|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Racism controversy==\nAround 41% of the population of Bolivia identifies itself as [[Indigenous peoples in Bolivia|indigenous]]<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/15/world/americas/morales-bolivia-Indigenous-racism.html |title=Ethnic Rifts in Bolivia Burst Into View With Fall of Evo Morales |date=15 November 2019 |agency=The New York Times}}</ref> and the population often encounters discrimination regarding their social status in Bolivia, mainly related to poverty and ethnic background.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/could-bolivias-current-politics-be-fueling-indigenous-discrimination |title=Could Bolivia's current politics be fueling indigenous discrimination? |last= |first= |date=25 November 2019 |website=[[PBS NewsHour]] |language=en-us |access-date=3 December 2019}}</ref> Following the 2006 election of Evo Morales, the first indigenous president of Bolivia, polarization between the indigenous peoples and others increased<ref name=\":5\" /> as Bolivia's political system shifted from left-right politics to indigenous-urbanist politics.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Faguet |first=Jean-Paul |date=June 2019 |title=Revolution from Below: Cleavage Displacement and the Collapse of Elite Politics in Bolivia |url= |journal=[[Politics & Society]] |volume=47 |issue=2 |pages=205-250 |quote=Politics shifted from a conventional left-right axis of competition, unsuited to Bolivian society, to an ethnic/rural\u2013cosmopolitan/urban axis closely aligned with its major social cleavage.|via= }}</ref>\n\nThrough social media, \u00c1\u00f1ez has made remarks<ref name=\"elcomercio\">{{cite news |url=https://elcomercio.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/jeanine-anez-estos-son-los-agresivos-tuits-contra-originarios-e-indigenas-que-borro-la-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-noticia/ |title=Estos son los agresivos tuits contra \"originarios\" e \"ind\u00edgenas\" que borr\u00f3 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la presidenta de Bolivia |date=15 November 2019 |agency=Redaccion El Comercio}}</ref> towards indigenous peoples that have been described as \"racist\" by ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref name=\"guardian\" /> \"anti-indigenous\" by [[Agence France-Press]],<ref name=\"afp\">{{cite news |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/these-are-anti-indigenous-tweets-bolivias-interim-president-deleted |title=These are the anti-indigenous tweets that Bolivia's interim president deleted |date=16 November 2019 |agency=Agence France-Presse (AFP)}}</ref> and \"provocative\" by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> On [[Twitter]], \u00c1\u00f1ez called the [[Aymara people]]'s [[Willkakuti|New Year celebration]] \"satanic\" and said that \"nobody can replace God\", and has implied that indigenous people were not genuine for wearing shoes.<ref name=\"afp\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> She would later state \"I\u2019ve seen a couple of tweets that I never wrote and that we already stated were false\" and that she never made \"ill-intentioned\" comments.<ref name=\":5\" /> In the opening days of her presidency, [[Mar\u00eda Galindo]], an outspoken critic of Morales, described the government of \u00c1\u00f1ez as \"anti-indigenous.\"<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 November 2019}}</ref> Kathryn Ledebur, director of the Andean Information Network, stated that \"there\u2019s a reason to raise the issue\" of racism and polarization following the rise of \u00c1\u00f1ez.\n\nAs acting president, \u00c1\u00f1ez has stated that she would keep the [[wiphala]], the flag of indigenous Bolivian communities, as a co-official [[flag of Bolivia]], as it had been under Morales, declaring that she was committed to the fundamental task of \"highlighting the unity [of the] plural and diverse\" nation of Bolivia.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/11/jeanine-anez-instruye-que-junto-a-la-sagrada-tricolor-se-mantenga-la-wiphala/ |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez instruye que junto a la sagrada tricolor se mantenga la wiphala |website=eju.tv |date=12 November 2019}}</ref> In addition to the whipala, the [[patuj\u00fa]] is displayed prominently.<ref>https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156526_colocan-la-bandera-de-la-flor-del-patuju-junto-a-la-wiphala-y-la-tricolor-en-palacio-quemado</ref> The patuj\u00fa is a symbol of the Eastern indigenous peoples of Bolivia and of [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]], Bolivia's largest city. This flag was also adopted by indigenous opposition to Morales during the [[Isiboro_S%C3%A9cure_National_Park_and_Indigenous_Territory|TIPNIS]] protests.<ref>https://radiopatuju.blogspot.com/2012/05/imagenes-por-el-tipnis-no.html</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> On 26 November 2019, she was presented with and wore a red poncho (a traditional Andean garment worn by community leaders) by representatives of the indigenous community on the inauguration of [[Rafael Quispe]] as director of the Fund for Indigenous Development.<ref>https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20191126/anez-viste-poncho-andino-obsequiado-comunarios</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez is married to [[H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal]], a Colombian politician in the [[Colombian Conservative Party]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=RESULTADO CORPORACI\u00d3N |url=https://elecciones.caracol.com.co/candidatos/senado/partido-conservador-colombiano |website=Caracol Radio |accessdate=14 November 2019|date=26 October 2019}}</ref> She comes from a poor [[mestiza]] background.<ref name=\"\u201cveconomist\u201d\">{{cite news|author=|title= Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|url= https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/07/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman|work=[[The Economist]]|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links\n|wikt=no|commonscat=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|n=no|q=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|s=no|author=no|b=no|v=no\n|voy=no|d=Q16581287|m=no|mw=no|species=no|species_author=no\n}}\n*[http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez]\n*[https://www.cidob.org/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_sur/bolivia/jeanine_anez_chavez Biography by CIDOB] \n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Evo Morales]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Bolivia]]|order=Interim|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of Bolivia}}\n{{Heads of State of the South America}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anez, Jeanine}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian Christians]]\n[[Category:Female heads of government]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:People from Beni Department]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women presidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Interim President of Bolivia since 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{spanish name|[[\u00c1\u00f1ez]]|[[Ch\u00e1vez (surname)|Ch\u00e1vez]]}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez\n| image               = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez.jpg\n| caption             = \u00c1\u00f1ez in 2016\n| order = 66th \n| office              = President of Bolivia\n| term_start          = 12 November 2019\n| term_end            = \n| vicepresident       = <!-- ''None'' -->\n| predecessor         = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[President pro tempore of the Community of Latin American and Caribbean States|President pro tempore of CELAC]]\n| term_start1         = 12 November 2019\n| term_end1           = 8 January 2020{{Efn|CELAC ''pro tempore'' presidency is assigned to countries and it automatically passes to the next president after elections. After the [[2019 Bolivian political crisis]], Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez would become ''pro tempore'' president of CELAC. However, Mexico called for a new CELAC summit on its own. Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez denounced that the summit should be called for by Bolivia. As the result of this dispute, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez did not attend to the CELAC summit and did not formally pass the ''pro tempore'' presidency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elimparcial.com/mundo/Bolivia-no-asistira-al-cambio-de-presidencia-de-la-Celac-por-roces-con-Mexico-20191223-0073.html|title=Bolivia no asistir\u00e1 al cambio de presidencia de la Celac por roces con M\u00e9xico|work=El Imparcial|date=23 December 2019|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/es/mundo/bolivia-rechaza-que-m%C3%A9xico-convocara-a-reuni%C3%B3n-de-la-celac-sin-consultarle-previamente/1682226|title=Bolivia rechaza que M\u00e9xico convocara a reuni\u00f3n de la Celac sin consultarle previamente|work=Anadolu Agency|first=Sant\u0131ago|last=Serna Duque|date=24 December 2020|access-date=11 April 2020|language=es}}</ref>}}\n| predecessor1        = [[Evo Morales]]\n| successor1          = [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]]\n| office2             = [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly|Senator]] for [[Beni Department|Beni]]\n| term_start2         = 22 January 2010\n| term_end2           = 12 November 2019\n| office3             = [[Bolivian Constituent Assembly of 2006\u201307|Member of the Constituent Assembly]]\n| term_start3         = 6 August 2006\n| term_end3           = 6 August 2007\n| birth_name          = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1967|8|13}}\n| birth_place         = [[Trinidad, Bolivia|Trinidad]], [[Beni Department|Beni]], Bolivia\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| spouse              = H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal\n| party               = [[Democrat Social Movement]] [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]]\n| signature           = Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez'''<ref>{{citation |title=Entrevista Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v185AWdeDE0 |language=en |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> ({{IPA-es|\u025f\u029da\u02c8nine \u02c8a\u0272es}}; born 13 August 1967)<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date=16 October 2015 |website=C\u00e1mara de Senadores |language=es |accessdate=11 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111145518/https://web.senado.gob.bo/senadoras-es/jeanine-%C3%A1%C3%B1ez-ch%C3%A1vez |archivedate=11 November 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is a Bolivian politician and lawyer currently serving as the Interim [[President of Bolivia]] since November 2019, after the [[Evo Morales government resignation|resignation of the government of Evo Morales]]. Her interim term will end when [[2020 Bolivian general election|new elections]] take place on an as yet undetermined date in 2020.\n\nShe was previously an opposition [[Senate of Bolivia|senator]] from the northeastern [[Departments of Bolivia|department]] of [[Beni, Bolivia|Beni]], belonging to the centre-right [[Democrat Social Movement]]. Her political position has been described by journalists as [[right-wing]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization |first=Dan |last=Collyns |date=14 November 2019 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/jeanine-anez-declares-bolivia-interim-president-191112233635201.html |title=Jeanine Anez declares herself Bolivia interim president |date=12 November 2019 |website=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> and anti-[[Evo Morales|Morales]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cronista.com/internacionales/Bolivia-quien-es-Jeanine-Anez-Chavez-la-mujer-que-puede-quedar-al-mando-de-la-transicion-20191110-0019.html |title=Bolivia: qui\u00e9n es Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, la mujer que puede quedar al mando de la transici\u00f3n |date=11 November 2019 |website=El Cronista |trans-title=Bolivia: who is Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez, the woman who can be in charge of the transition |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html |title=After Morales' resignation, a question for Bolivia: Was this the democratic will, or a coup? |last=Faiola |first=Anthony |date= |website=[[The Washington Post]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111194058/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/after-morales-resignation-a-question-for-bolivia-was-this-the-democratic-will-or-a-coup/2019/11/11/ff36ce9a-040c-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html|archive-date=2019-11-11|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50399640 |title=Bolivian senator assumes interim presidency |last= |first= |date=13 November 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez has a graduate degree in law and legal sciences from the Autonomous University of the Beni Jos\u00e9 Ballivi\u00e1n.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Career==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez passed the bar in 1991.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was formerly a media presenter<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eltiempo.com/mundo/perfil-de-jeanine-anez-nueva-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-432904 |title=\u00bfQui\u00e9n es Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la nueva presidenta interina de Bolivia? |first=Casa Editorial El |last=Tiempo |date=13 November 2019 |location=Colombia |language=es |website=[[ElTiempo.com]]}}</ref> and director at Totalvision.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Constituent Assembly (2006\u20132008)===\nBetween 2006 and 2008, she served as a constituent assemblywoman for the drafting of the new constitutional charter. She was a member of the Constituent Assembly for the commission of organization and structure of the country, also working as part of the Judiciary.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Senate (2010\u20132019)===\nIn 2010, she was elected to the [[Bolivian Senate|Senate]] as a member of the party [[Plan Progress for Bolivia \u2013 National Convergence|Plan Progress for Bolivia-National Convergence]] (P.P.B - C.N), representing the Department of Beni in the National Assembly.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez |date= |access-date=21 April 2014 |publisher=vicepresidencia.gob.bo |language=es |format= |quote= }}</ref> She ran for governor of Beni in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Jeanine-Anez-precandidata-gobernacion-Beni_0_1697830274.html |title=La senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez surge como primera precandidata opositora a la gobernaci\u00f3n de Beni; el MSM apunta a una tercera opci\u00f3n |last=Corz |first=Carlos |date=1 October 2012 |website=La Raz\u00f3n |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy 2019, she was the second vice president of the Senate, and her alternate was Franklin Valdivia Leigue.<ref name=\":0\" /> This role placed her fifth in the [[President of Bolivia#Current line of succession|line of succession to the presidency]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Before the presidential elections in 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez had questioned the reliability of opinion polls, based on unclear methods and inconsistent results.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/8/19/piden-informe-escrito-al-tse-por-la-encuestadora-viaciencia-228016.html |title=Piden informe escrito al TSE por la encuestadora ViaCiencia |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===<span id=\"Interim president of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)\"></span>Interim President of Bolivia (2019\u2013present)===\n\nOn 10 November, Morales and his vice president, [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]], [[Evo Morales government resignation|resigned from office]] after pressure from political opponents and civic groups and losing support from former political allies, the police and the [[Armed Forces of Bolivia|military]];<ref name=\"Londo\u00f1o\">Ernesto Londo\u00f1o, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/evo-morales-bolivia.html Bolivian Leader Evo Morales Steps Down], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (10 November 2019).</ref>. This was followed by the resignation of [[Adriana Salvatierra Arriaza]], the president of the [[Bolivian Senate]], who was next in the constitutional line of succession<ref name=\"GuerreroAndone\">Kay Guerrero & Dakin Andone, [https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/10/americas/bolivia-new-election-audit/index.html Bolivian President Evo Morales steps down following accusations of election fraud], CNN (10 November 2019).</ref>\u2014leading to a situation where all constitutional successors were exhausted. The role of acting President of the Senate would normally fall to the vice-president of the Senate, Rub\u00e9n Medinaceli, but since he also had resigned, the position fell to A\u00f1ez as second vice-president of the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/76278_salvatierra-asume-pide-que-haya-mas-inclusion-de-mujeres-y-jovenes|title=Salvatierra sworn in; Calls for more inclusion of women and young people|website=El Deber|date=18 January 2019|language=es|author=Jes\u00fas Alanoca Paco}}</ref> Thus A\u00f1ez became the highest-ranking official in the line of succession to the presidency of Bolivia and stated an acceptance to fill the role if needed. The succession was not automatic, however, as the Legislative Assembly would need to hold emergency meetings to accept the abdications of the President and Vice-President and determine who was next in line due to the lack of constitutional guidance.<ref name=\"vicepresidente1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-50370125 |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez en proceso de ratificaci\u00f3n tras renuncia del Presidente, Vicepresidente, Presidente del Senado y Presidente de la C\u00e1mara de Diputados de Bolivia |editor=BBC News Mundo |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez could not attend an emergency assembly until the day after Morales' resignation, as she was in Beni and there were no Sunday flights from there to the capital of [[La Paz]].<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nOn 11 November, A\u00f1ez arrived at [[El Alto International Airport|La Paz-El Alto airport]] and was taken in a military helicopter to a nearby Air Force base. From there, she traveled to the Bolivian Senate. At 4pm, an emergency vote took place to formally accept the resignations of the previous day. <ref name=\"Huff-Post\">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.fr/entry/apres-la-demission-devo-morales-les-insoumis-denoncent-un-coup-detat_fr_5dc91fa7e4b00927b236112e |title=Apr\u00e8s la d\u00e9mission d'Evo Morales, les insoumis d\u00e9noncent un \"coup d'\u00c9tat\" |date=11 November 2019 |website=Le Huffington Post}}</ref> Morales' MAS party, which still held a majority in the upper chamber, boycotted this vote. Constitutional experts Paul Coca and Israel Alanoca stated that, while the normal quorum would have been desirable for purpose of quelling accusations of a coup d'etat, there was no specific regulation to deal with the resignation of leaders and an emergency vote on the grounds of human rights concerns and establishing social peace would be legally valid.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/11/si-no-hay-quorum-en-la-alp-se-puede-apelar-al-voto-de-urgencia-237110.html|title=If there is no quorum in the ALP, an emergency vote can be applied|language=es|date=11 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn the evening of 12 November, per article 169 of the [[Constitution of Bolivia]], \u00c1\u00f1ez was declared acting [[president of Bolivia]] in front of a session of the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156411_anez-asume-la-presidencia-de-bolivia-ante-vacancia-y-aplicando-la-sucesion-constitucional|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez asume la Presidencia de Bolivia ante vacancia y aplicando la sucesi\u00f3n constitucional|trans-title=\u00c1\u00f1ez assumes the Presidency of Bolivia due to vacancy and applying the constitutional succession|website=El Deber|language=es|access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> This vote was also boycotted by MAS, who dubbed the vote \"illegal\". <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/12/anez-asume-la-presidencia-para-pacificar-el-pais-237195.html|title=Anez assumes the presidency to pacify the country|language=es|date=12 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/12/evo-morales-arrives-mexico-bolivia-power-vacuum |title=Bolivia: Jeanine A\u00f1ez claims presidency after ousting of Evo Morales |location=La Paz |first1=Jo |last1=Tuckman |first2=Dan |last2=Collyns |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 }}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/13/americas/bolivia-political-unrest-intl-hnk/index.html |title=Bolivian senator declares herself acting president -- but she may be on shaky ground |first1=Joshua |last1=Berlinger |first2=Gustavo |last2=Vald\u00e9s |website=CNN |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez obtained the favourable vote of the remaining parties, a third part of the parliament. <ref>{{cite news |title=La senadora Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez se proclama presidenta de Bolivia sin qu\u00f3rum en el Parlamento |url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/12/america/1573566340_453048.html |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=13 November 2019 |accessdate=13 November 2019|issn=1134-6582|language=es|first=Francesco|last=Manetto}}</ref> The move was later upheld by the [[Plurinational Constitutional Court]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eldeber.com.bo/156414_tcp-avala-sucesion-constitucional-en-la-presidencia|title=TCP avala sucesi\u00f3n constitucional en la Presidencia |trans-title=TCP uphelds constitutional succession in the Presidency |website=El Deber |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019 }}</ref> \n\nAfter taking office, the governments of [[Canada]], [[Brazil]], the [[European Union]], [[Russia]] and the [[United States]] recognized \u00c1\u00f1ez as the acting president of Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Canada will 'support' Bolivian opposition government |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/bolivia-canada-anez-government-1.5360138 |work=CBC News |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>{{when|date=December 2019}}<!-- the timing of this recognition should be included in the prose -->\n\nOn 13 November Salvatierra contended that her resignation was not valid since it had not been accepted by the Senate, and therefore, \u00c1\u00f1ez should not be able to assume the Presidency via becoming President of the Senate.<ref name=\"dispute\">{{cite news |title=Presidenta de Senado boliviano denuncia presi\u00f3n a dirigentes |url=https://www.telesurtv.net/news/bolivia-presidenta-senado-denuncia-presion-dirigentes-20191113-0021.html |accessdate=14 November 2019 |work=www.telesurtv.net |agency=teleSUR |date=13 November 2019 |language=es}}</ref> This prompted a further session on the Senate on 14 November, this time with the involvement of MAS, that reaffirmed Salvatierra's resignation more formally and elected M\u00f3nica Eva Copa from the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] as the new president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol%C3%ADtica/eva-copa-es-la-nueva-presidenta-del-senado|language=es|title=Eva Copa is the new president of the Senate|date=15 November 2019|website=www.atb.com.bo}}</ref>\n\nAmid a pledge to \"rebuild democracy\", A\u00f1ez unveiled her new [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]]. Her senior ministers included prominent businesspeople from [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]]. The first eleven members of her cabinet did not include any members of the [[indigenous peoples in Bolivia]], which ''[[The Guardian]]'' described as a sign that she did \"not intend to reach across the country's deep political and ethnic divide\". Later appointments of the remaining positions would include two indigenous members. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Anez-completa-gabinete-ministra-Alto_0_3257674272.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez posesiona cinco nuevos ministros; Yujra besa la wiphala y va por di\u00e1logo con El Alto - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/ministros-posesion-bolivia-anez_0_3260074003.html|title=A\u00f1ez posesiona a Carlos Huallpa en Miner\u00eda y a Virginia Patty Torres en Educaci\u00f3n - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref> Morales' cabinet had also included two indigenous persons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/especial01/2017/1/22/gabinete-tuvo-rostros-indigenas-pero-pocos-ministros-poder-124588.html|title=Gabinete tuvo rostros ind\u00edgenas, pero pocos ministros con poder - Diario Pagina Siete|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|access-date=23 December 2019}}</ref>\nHer designated interior minister vowed to \"hunt down\" his predecessor, which reportedly stroked fears of a \"[[witch-hunt]]\" against members of Morales' administration.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization |last=Collyns |first=Dan |date=14 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 November 2019 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She further stated that Morales would not be permitted to run in an upcoming election for a fourth term, should he return to Bolivia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-bolivias-interim-leader-says-evo-morales-cant-run-in-new-election/ |title=Bolivia's interim leader says Evo Morales can't run in new election |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-interim-president-bars-morales-from-new-elections/a-51259511 |title=Bolivia: Interim president bars Morales from new elections {{!}} DW {{!}} 15 November 2019  |last=Welle (www.dw.com) |first=Deutsche |website=DW.COM |language=en-GB |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe new interim government of president Jeanine A\u00f1ez has denounced foreign influence in the country since taking power, naming Colombians, Peruvians, Cubans and Venezuelans at different times. Her government has blamed foreigners for provoking violent clashes during more than a month of post-election violence in [[Bolivia]] that has left dozens of people dead. Police arrested an Argentine national, 44-year-old Facundo Morales Schoenfeld, in the eastern province of Santa Cruz, who is a former member of the [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] (FARC) and was participating among the protesters in [[Yapacan\u00ed]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/americas/bolivia-unveils-anti-terror-unit-to-fight-threatening-foreign-groups |title=Bolivia unveils anti-terror unit to fight 'threatening' foreign groups |date=4 December 2019 |website=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 December, \u00c1\u00f1ez stated that she would not be a candidate or support any candidate in the upcoming presidential election.<ref>[https://rpp.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/bolivia-jeanine-anez-no-postulara-a-la-presidencia-segun-el-gobierno-interino-noticia-1233337 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez no postular\u00e1 a la Presidencia de Bolivia, seg\u00fan el Gobierno interino.] Publicado el 5 de diciembre de 2019. Consultado el 8 de diciembre de 2019.</ref> This was further reiterated on 15 January 2020 by Minister for the Presidency [[:w:es:Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez|Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], who said that \"[\u00c1\u00f1ez] will not be a candidate. The President has stated on several occasions, she will not be a candidate, this is a government of peace, transition, and management because you can not stop the state apparatus.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/jeanine-anez-presidencia-gobierno-elecciones-bolivia_0_3294870527.html| language=es|title=Government clarifies that Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez will not be a candidate for the Presidency}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 January 2020, the government decided to ratify the 22 January public holiday created by Morales to celebrate the founding of the [[Plurinational State of Bolivia]] via the 2009 constitution. On this day, the President of Bolivia normally addresses the nation, but doubt had been expressed whether this holiday would go ahead due to its strong political connection with Morales and MAS. In a public statement, however, minister for the Presidency [[Yerko N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], said \"January 22 is a holiday by presidential decree, we are going to respect that decree and our president is evaluating if she is going to make a report about the pillars of this government, which are transition, pacification and management.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/1/7/gobierno-ratifica-feriado-del-22-de-enero-anez-evalua-informe-de-gestion-242710.html | title=Government ratifies 22 January holiday and A\u00f1ez considers management address|language=es}}</ref>\n\nDespite her previous statements, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced her candidacy on 24 January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atb.com.bo/pol\u00edtica/jeanine-\u00e1\u00f1ez-confirma-candidatura-presidencial-para-las-elecciones-generales|title=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez confirma candidatura presidencial para las elecciones generales|date=24 January 2020|access-date=24 January 2020|website=ATBDigital|language=es-ES}}</ref> A survey reported in the Bolivian newspaper ''[[Los Tiempos]]'' indicated that, while 43% of respondents considered her to have done a \"good or very good\" job as interim president (compared to 27% bad or very bad), only 24% of respondents believed that she should stand as a candidate in the upcoming elections. In the same poll, 63% of respondents agreed with the statement that \"as interim president, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez should call elections and not take advantage of her power to become a presidential candidate.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20200126/encuesta-aprueban-gestion-anez-pero-rechazan-candidatura| title=Survey approves of \u00c1\u00f1ez's term as president, but rejects her candidacy.|language=es|date=26 January 2020}}</ref> Her running mate who was previously critical of her decision to stand as a presidential candidate is [[Samuel Doria Medina]], a former presidential candidate and leader of the centre-right [[National Unity Front]] party.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/05/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman| title=Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|date= 7 March 2020}}</ref>. They are standing under the newly formed [[Juntos (Bolivian political party)|Juntos]] alliance. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Unidad-Nacional-Sole-Vicepresidencia-Juntos_0_3304469555.html|title=\u00c1\u00f1ez and Doria Medina seal alliance and become presidential running mates| language=es|date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince early March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez has implemented numerous controls concerning the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bolivia|coronavirus pandemic]] including closing all borders, prohibiting all international and interdepartmental flights, a strict nationwide curfew and restricting driving to those transporting foods and supplies and those carrying out essential services. This crisis has also resulted in the postponement of the upcoming [[2020 Bolivian general election]], the delay having been agreed upon by all parties involved.\n\n== Political views ==\nA\u00f1ez is described as a [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-idUSKBN1XM1NV |title=Bolivian Senate head assumes interim presidency; Morales' loyalists object |date=13 November 2019 |work=Reuters |access-date=15 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-bolivian-senator-declares-herself-president-morales-denounces-coup |title=Bolivian senator declares herself interim president, Morales slams 'coup' |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> [[Religious conservatism|religious conservative]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/bolivia-s-new-leader-religious-conservative-jeanine-ez-chavez-faces-n1082426 |title=Bolivia's new leader, religious conservative Jeanine A\u00f1ez Chavez, faces daunting challenges |website=NBC News |language=en |access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/14/bolivia-interim-leader-recognises-guaido-legitimate-venezuelan/ |title=Bolivia interim leader recognises Guaido as legitimate Venezuelan leader as balance shifts |last=Staff |first=Our Foreign |date=14 November 2019 |work=The Telegraph |access-date=15 November 2019 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and has been a critic of Evo Morales.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bolivia-senator-jeanine-anez-declares-herself-interim-president/a-51218963 |title=Bolivia: Senator Jeanine Anez declares herself interim president {{!}} DW {{!}} 12 November 2019 |last= |first= |date= |website=Deutsche Welle |language=en-GB |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Drugs===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez has spoken out against the proliferation of drug trafficking in South America.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2017/10/20/narcotrafico-anez-llama-canalla-romero-dice-sobrino-responsable-actos-156480.html |title=Narcotr\u00e1fico: A\u00f1ez llama \"canalla\" a Romero y dice que su sobrino es responsable de sus actos |last= |first= |date= |website=Diario Pagina Siete |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, her nephew was arrested in Brazil for smuggling 480 kilos of drugs. The security minister [[Carlos Romero (Bolivian politician)|Carlos Romero]] criticized \u00c1\u00f1ez and said that her position in the senate was \"rogue\" because of the relationship; \u00c1\u00f1ez responded by saying that she is not responsible for her nephew's actions, and criticized Romero because of his position in the government by saying that he is \"responsible for the growth of drug trafficking\". It was later revealed that another Bolivian arrested with drugs at the same time was the nephew of another politician, this time belonging to the MAS ruling party.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===Prison services===\nIn early 2019, \u00c1\u00f1ez called for an investigation into prison wardens in Beni after speaking to victims of rape and abuse on the part of guards. She aimed to set a precedent to bring in new legislation that can be upheld.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/03/senadora-jeanine-anez-pide-al-gobierno-investigar-todas-carceletas-del-beni/ |title=Senadora Jeanine A\u00f1ez pide al Gobierno investigar todas carceletas del Beni |website=eju.tv |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nShe describes herself as a [[Christianity|Christian]] and held up a large Bible while declaring herself the interim president; this was described by ''The Guardian'' as an \"explicit rebuke\" of Morales, who has a strained [[Evo Morales and the Roman Catholic Church|history with the Catholic Church]] and has expressed support for indigenous religious traditions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191113-jeanine-anez-stand-in-president-vowing-to-pacify-bolivia |title=Jeanine Anez: stand-in president vowing to 'pacify' Bolivia |date=13 November 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/13/jeanine-anez-bolivia-president-promises-new-elections |title=Bolivia's interim president Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez promises new elections |last=Collyns |first=Dan |date=13 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |access-date=13 November 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Under Morales, a new [[Constitution of Bolivia|Constitution]] was [[2009 Bolivian constitutional referendum|approved by referendum]] that gave Christianity equal status to other religions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-11/bolivia-faces-power-vacuum-and-more-chaos-after-morales-quits |title=Senator Brandishing Giant Bible Takes Over Bolivia Presidency |date=11 November 2019 |website=Bloomberg |language=en |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> A 2018 survey found that 70% of Bolivians identified as Catholic and 17.2% as Protestant of some form. 9.3% were non-religious.<ref>https://www.statista.com/statistics/1066911/religious-affiliation-in-bolivia/</ref> Political analyst Carlos Cordero states that \u201cShe is a believer, but she does not use her religiosity politically, she expresses it, she lives it.\u201d<ref>https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/12/30/las-quince-diferencias-en-el-estilo-de-gobernar-de-jeanine-anez-morales-241950.html</ref>\n\n===Venezuela===\n\u00c1\u00f1ez recognized [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] as acting president of Venezuela in the [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis]], 24 hours after taking office.<ref name=\"Alberto\">{{cite web |url=https://albertonews.com/principales/ultima-hora-bolivia-reconoce-a-juan-guaido-como-presidente-e-de-venezuela/ |title=Bolivia reconoce a Juan Guaid\u00f3 como presidente (E) de Venezuela |date=13 November 2019 |website=Albertonews.com |language=es |access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref> Her interim government also severed diplomatic relations with Venezuela's Maduro government, giving its diplomats 72 hours to leave the country.<ref name=\"lapiensa\">{{cite web |url=https://latinoamericapiensa.com/la-politica-internacional-de-anez-anuncio-la-salida-de-bolivia-del-alba-de-la-unasur-y-rompio-relaciones-con-venezuela/21065/ |title=La pol\u00edtica internacional de A\u00f1ez: anunci\u00f3 la salida de Bolivia del Alba, de la Unasur y rompi\u00f3 relaciones con Venezuela |language=es |website=Latinomerica Piensa |date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-bolivia-election-venezuela/bolivas-interim-government-to-ask-venezuelan-diplomats-to-leave-the-country-idUKKBN1XP23U |title=Boliva's interim government to ask Venezuelan diplomats to leave the country |website=Reuters |date=15 November 2019}}</ref> \u00c1\u00f1ez has also called on Guaid\u00f3 to appoint the new Venezuelan Ambassador to Bolivia, \"who will be recognized immediately by our government.\"<ref name=\"Alberto\"/>\n\nA month later, her government announced Bolivia's entry into the [[Lima Group]], a regional bloc established in 2017 with the purpose of finding a way out of the [[Crisis in Venezuela|Venezuelan crisis]]. The Bolivian foreign ministry said in a statement that it hoped to \u201ccontribute to a peaceful, democratic and constitutional solution to the crisis in Venezuela, which must be guided by the Venezuelan people.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | last1=Sigal | first1=Lucila | title=Bolivia announces entry into Lima Group to resolve Venezuelan crisis | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivia-announces-entry-into-lima-group-to-resolve-venezuelan-crisis-idUSKBN1YQ0JM | date=22 December 2019 | work=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref> On the same month, the interim government announced that they would give refuge to 200 Venezuelans \"who have fled their country for reasons of political order, of political persecution promoted by the [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] government.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/es/bolivia-dar%C3%A1-refugio-a-200-venezolanos-que-huyeron-por-persecuci%C3%B3n-pol%C3%ADtica/a-51665845|title=Bolivia will shelter 200 Venezuelans who fled for \"political persecution\"|last=|first=|date=13 December 2019|work=[[Deutsch Welle]]|access-date=4 January 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n===Violence against women and children===\nOn 6 February 2020, she invited the people of Bolivia to attend a march in Santa Cruz in support of the fight against violence against women and children, an issue increasingly highlighted by the Bolivian press. <ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/rascacielos/2020/3/8/feminicidios-en-bolivia-suenos-robados-248613.html|language=es|date=8 March 2020|title=Feminicides in Bolivia: Stolen Dreams}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/2/6/anez-pide-denunciar-la-violencia-contra-mujeres-ninos-en-una-marcha-245817.html|date=6 February 2020| title=A\u00f1ez asks to denounce violence against women and children in a march|language=es}}</ref>\n\nOn [[International Women's Day]], 8 March 2020, \u00c1\u00f1ez announced a $100 million investment in the fight against violence against women, She declared 2020 as the  Year of the Fight Against Feminicide and Infanticide in Bolivia, saying \"I am the worst news for all those murderers of women, users of violence, abusers, stalkers and rapists, because I will not get tired of closing against these aggressors\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.la-razon.com/sociedad/mujer-bolivia-anez-presidenta-violencia-genero_0_3326667313.html| title=\u00c1\u00f1ez: 'I will give everything to end gender violence'|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/sociedad/2020/3/10/violencia-anez-lanza-plan-con-una-inversion-de-us-100-millones-249125.html|title=Violence: A\u00f1ez launches plan with an investment of $ us 100 million|language=es|date=8 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Racism controversy==\nAround 41% of the population of Bolivia identifies itself as [[Indigenous peoples in Bolivia|indigenous]]<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/15/world/americas/morales-bolivia-Indigenous-racism.html |title=Ethnic Rifts in Bolivia Burst Into View With Fall of Evo Morales |date=15 November 2019 |agency=The New York Times}}</ref> and the population often encounters discrimination regarding their social status in Bolivia, mainly related to poverty and ethnic background.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/could-bolivias-current-politics-be-fueling-indigenous-discrimination |title=Could Bolivia's current politics be fueling indigenous discrimination? |last= |first= |date=25 November 2019 |website=[[PBS NewsHour]] |language=en-us |access-date=3 December 2019}}</ref> Following the 2006 election of Evo Morales, the first indigenous president of Bolivia, polarization between the indigenous peoples and others increased<ref name=\":5\" /> as Bolivia's political system shifted from left-right politics to indigenous-urbanist politics.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Faguet |first=Jean-Paul |date=June 2019 |title=Revolution from Below: Cleavage Displacement and the Collapse of Elite Politics in Bolivia |url= |journal=[[Politics & Society]] |volume=47 |issue=2 |pages=205-250 |quote=Politics shifted from a conventional left-right axis of competition, unsuited to Bolivian society, to an ethnic/rural\u2013cosmopolitan/urban axis closely aligned with its major social cleavage.|via= }}</ref>\n\nThrough social media, \u00c1\u00f1ez has made remarks<ref name=\"elcomercio\">{{cite news |url=https://elcomercio.pe/mundo/latinoamerica/jeanine-anez-estos-son-los-agresivos-tuits-contra-originarios-e-indigenas-que-borro-la-presidenta-interina-de-bolivia-noticia/ |title=Estos son los agresivos tuits contra \"originarios\" e \"ind\u00edgenas\" que borr\u00f3 Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez, la presidenta de Bolivia |date=15 November 2019 |agency=Redaccion El Comercio}}</ref> towards indigenous peoples that have been described as \"racist\" by ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref name=\"guardian\" /> \"anti-indigenous\" by [[Agence France-Press]],<ref name=\"afp\">{{cite news |url=https://factcheck.afp.com/these-are-anti-indigenous-tweets-bolivias-interim-president-deleted |title=These are the anti-indigenous tweets that Bolivia's interim president deleted |date=16 November 2019 |agency=Agence France-Presse (AFP)}}</ref> and \"provocative\" by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> On [[Twitter]], \u00c1\u00f1ez called the [[Aymara people]]'s [[Willkakuti|New Year celebration]] \"satanic\" and said that \"nobody can replace God\", and has implied that indigenous people were not genuine for wearing shoes.<ref name=\"afp\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> She would later state \"I\u2019ve seen a couple of tweets that I never wrote and that we already stated were false\" and that she never made \"ill-intentioned\" comments.<ref name=\":5\" /> In the opening days of her presidency, [[Mar\u00eda Galindo]], an outspoken critic of Morales, described the government of \u00c1\u00f1ez as \"anti-indigenous.\"<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news |title=Bolivia president's initial indigenous-free cabinet heightens polarization|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/14/bolivia-president-jeanine-anez-cabinet-indigenous |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 November 2019}}</ref> Kathryn Ledebur, director of the Andean Information Network, stated that \"there\u2019s a reason to raise the issue\" of racism and polarization following the rise of \u00c1\u00f1ez.\n\nAs acting president, \u00c1\u00f1ez has stated that she would keep the [[wiphala]], the flag of indigenous Bolivian communities, as a co-official [[flag of Bolivia]], as it had been under Morales, declaring that she was committed to the fundamental task of \"highlighting the unity [of the] plural and diverse\" nation of Bolivia.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://eju.tv/2019/11/jeanine-anez-instruye-que-junto-a-la-sagrada-tricolor-se-mantenga-la-wiphala/ |title=Jeanine A\u00f1ez instruye que junto a la sagrada tricolor se mantenga la wiphala |website=eju.tv |date=12 November 2019}}</ref> In addition to the whipala, the [[patuj\u00fa]] is displayed prominently.<ref>https://www.eldeber.com.bo/156526_colocan-la-bandera-de-la-flor-del-patuju-junto-a-la-wiphala-y-la-tricolor-en-palacio-quemado</ref> The patuj\u00fa is a symbol of the Eastern indigenous peoples of Bolivia and of [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]], Bolivia's largest city. This flag was also adopted by indigenous opposition to Morales during the [[Isiboro_S%C3%A9cure_National_Park_and_Indigenous_Territory|TIPNIS]] protests.<ref>https://radiopatuju.blogspot.com/2012/05/imagenes-por-el-tipnis-no.html</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> On 26 November 2019, she was presented with and wore a red poncho (a traditional Andean garment worn by community leaders) by representatives of the indigenous community on the inauguration of [[Rafael Quispe]] as director of the Fund for Indigenous Development.<ref>https://www.lostiempos.com/actualidad/pais/20191126/anez-viste-poncho-andino-obsequiado-comunarios</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\u00c1\u00f1ez is married to [[H\u00e9ctor Hernando Hincapi\u00e9 Carvajal]], a Colombian politician in the [[Colombian Conservative Party]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=RESULTADO CORPORACI\u00d3N |url=https://elecciones.caracol.com.co/candidatos/senado/partido-conservador-colombiano |website=Caracol Radio |accessdate=14 November 2019|date=26 October 2019}}</ref> She comes from a poor [[mestiza]] background.<ref name=\"\u201cveconomist\u201d\">{{cite news|author=|title= Bolivia after the ouster of Evo Morales, a leftist strongman|url= https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2020/03/07/bolivia-after-the-ouster-of-evo-morales-a-leftist-strongman|work=[[The Economist]]|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links\n|wikt=no|commonscat=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|n=no|q=Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez|s=no|author=no|b=no|v=no\n|voy=no|d=Q16581287|m=no|mw=no|species=no|species_author=no\n}}\n*[http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/spip.php?page=parlamentario&id_parlamentario=159 Jeanine A\u00f1ez Ch\u00e1vez]\n*[https://www.cidob.org/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_sur/bolivia/jeanine_anez_chavez Biography by CIDOB] \n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Evo Morales]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Bolivia]]|order=Interim|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of Bolivia}}\n{{Heads of State of the South America}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anez, Jeanine}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian Christians]]\n[[Category:Female heads of government]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:People from Beni Department]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Senate of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Women presidents]]\n", "name_user": "Electos242", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeanine_%C3%81%C3%B1ez"}
{"title_page": "Lydian augmented scale", "text_new": "[[File:Lydian augmented scale on C.png|thumb|right|300px|Lydian augmented scale on C {{audio|Christalydian scale on C.mid|Play}}.]]\n{{Infobox musical scale\n| name          = Christalydian scale\n| first_pitch   = [[unison (music)|C]]\n| second_pitch  = [[major second|D]]\n| third_pitch   = [[major third|E]]\n| fourth_pitch  = [[tritone#eleventh harmonic|F{{music|#}}]]\n| fifth_pitch   = [[augmented fifth|G{{music|#}}]]\n| sixth_pitch   = [[major sixth|A]]\n| seventh_pitch = [[major seventh|B]]\n| pitch_classes = 7\n| modes         = [[Ascending melodic minor|I]], [[Dorian b2 scale|II]], III, [[Acoustic scale|IV]], [[Aeolian dominant scale|V]], [[Half diminished scale|VI]], [[Altered scale|VII]]\n| Forte number  = 7-34\n| complement    = 5-34\n}}\n\nIn [[music]], the '''Lydian augmented scale''' ('''Lydian {{music|#}}5 scale''') is the third [[musical mode|mode]] of the ascending [[melodic minor scale]] or [[jazz minor scale]].\n\nStarting on C, the notes would be as follows:\n C  - D  - E  - F{{music|#}} - G{{music|#}} - A  - B  - C<!--Template:Music is note used to allow fixed width-->\nGenerically the whole and half steps are:\n -  W -  W -  W -  W -  H -  W -  H -\n\nThe scale may be thought of as a major scale with an [[augmented fourth]] and [[augmented fifth|fifth]], or as the [[relative key|relative]] to the [[melodic minor]] ascending scale (C Lydian augmented and A melodic minor ascending share the same notes).\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jazz scale]]\n*[[Lydian chord]]\n*[[Lydian mode]]\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Jerry Coker|Coker, Jerry]] (1997). ''Jerry Coker's Complete Method for Improvisation'', p.&nbsp;36. {{ISBN|978-0-7692-1856-4}}.\n*Hewitt, Michael. 2013. ''Musical Scales of the World''. The Note Tree. {{ISBN|978-0957547001}}.\n\n==External links==\n\n{{scales|state=uncollapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Heptatonic scales]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Lydian augmented scale on C.png|thumb|right|300px|Lydian augmented scale on C {{audio|Lydian augmented scale on C.mid|Play}}.]]\n{{Infobox musical scale\n| name          = Lydian augmented scale\n| first_pitch   = [[unison (music)|C]]\n| second_pitch  = [[major second|D]]\n| third_pitch   = [[major third|E]]\n| fourth_pitch  = [[tritone#eleventh harmonic|F{{music|#}}]]\n| fifth_pitch   = [[augmented fifth|G{{music|#}}]]\n| sixth_pitch   = [[major sixth|A]]\n| seventh_pitch = [[major seventh|B]]\n| pitch_classes = 7\n| modes         = [[Ascending melodic minor|I]], [[Dorian b2 scale|II]], III, [[Acoustic scale|IV]], [[Aeolian dominant scale|V]], [[Half diminished scale|VI]], [[Altered scale|VII]]\n| Forte number  = 7-34\n| complement    = 5-34\n}}\n\nIn [[music]], the '''Lydian augmented scale''' ('''Lydian {{music|#}}5 scale''') is the third [[musical mode|mode]] of the ascending [[melodic minor scale]] or [[jazz minor scale]].\n\nStarting on C, the notes would be as follows:\n C  - D  - E  - F{{music|#}} - G{{music|#}} - A  - B  - C<!--Template:Music is note used to allow fixed width-->\nGenerically the whole and half steps are:\n -  W -  W -  W -  W -  H -  W -  H -\n\nThe scale may be thought of as a major scale with an [[augmented fourth]] and [[augmented fifth|fifth]], or as the [[relative key|relative]] to the [[melodic minor]] ascending scale (C Lydian augmented and A melodic minor ascending share the same notes).\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jazz scale]]\n*[[Lydian chord]]\n*[[Lydian mode]]\n\n==Sources==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Jerry Coker|Coker, Jerry]] (1997). ''Jerry Coker's Complete Method for Improvisation'', p.&nbsp;36. {{ISBN|978-0-7692-1856-4}}.\n*Hewitt, Michael. 2013. ''Musical Scales of the World''. The Note Tree. {{ISBN|978-0957547001}}.\n\n==External links==\n\n{{scales|state=uncollapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Heptatonic scales]]\n", "name_user": "73.58.155.186", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lydian_augmented_scale"}
{"title_page": "Intake ramp", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=January 2015}}\nAn '''intake ramp''' is a rectangular, plate-like device within the [[Components of jet engines#Air intakes|air intake]] of a [[jet engine]], designed to generate a number of [[shock wave]]s to aid the inlet compression process at [[supersonic]] speeds. The ramp sits at an acute angle to deflect the intake air from the longitudinal direction. At [[supersonic]] flight speeds, the deflection of the air stream creates a number of oblique shock waves at each change of gradient along at the ramp. Air crossing each shock wave suddenly slows to a lower [[Mach number]], thus increasing [[pressure]].\n\nIdeally, the first oblique shock wave should intercept the air intake lip, thus avoiding air spillage and pre-entry drag on the outer boundary of the deflected streamtube. For a fixed geometry intake at zero incidence, this condition can only be achieved at one particular flight Mach number, because the angle of the shock wave (to the longitudinal direction) becomes more acute with increasing aircraft speed.\n\nMore advanced supersonic intakes feature a ramp with a number of discrete changes of gradient in order to generate multiple oblique shock waves. In the case of [[Concorde]], the first (converging) intake ramp is followed by a diverging ramp. After the air passes the end of the first ramp it has become subsonic such that the diverging ramp further contributes towards the reduction in airstream velocity and consequently its increase in pressure. This intake design thus ensures excellent pressure recovery and contributes to Concorde's improved fuel efficiency whilst [[Supercruise|cruising supersonically]] at up to Mach 2.2 (beyond which airframe heating effects limit any further increase in speed).\n\nFor a fixed geometry it is feasible to use curved intakes without any shocks before the final normal shock.\nModern fighter jets (like the [[F-22 Raptor]]) have engines so powerful that top speed is not limited by them,\nthus spillage at the intake is acceptable and a lightweight fixed geometry chosen. The nacelle has a round outer lip to deflect spillage back into the longitudinal direction. The nacelle thus gets a very large cross section with more volume than needed for the engine and in the F-22 the nacelles are combined with the fuselage to create a large weapon bay, place for fuel, and a wide body, which generates some lift.\nModern jets have a horizontal ramp thus spillage at least produces some lift.\nIn the case of the F-22 the inlet has two ramps placed in a diamond shape, thus for most Mach- and thrust-conditions spillage occurs only at the aft / lower corner of that diamond.{{Or|date=June 2010}}\nIn the case of the F-22 the leading edges of the wing become supersonic at Mach 1.8 and certainly are as large a source of wave drag as the inlet.\n\nVariable geometry intakes, such as those on Concorde, vary the ramp angle to focus the series of oblique shock waves onto the intake lip, control of which is accomplished by complex non-linear control laws using the ramp void pressure (the pressure of the air in the gap between the two ramps) as a control input.\n\n==Intake gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Concordeintake.gif| Concorde ramps move to suit flight condition\nImage:Concorde Ramp.jpg| The ramps in two of the Concorde intakes are visible and clearly labelled as such.\nImage:F-14_3_Yokota_Tokyo.jpg| [[F-14]] with internal ramps forming upper surface of intake duct\nImage:North American XB-70 above runway ECN-792.jpg|Vertical ramps on inboard surface of intake duct [[XB-70]]\nImage:F-15E Strike Eagle is parked by a crew chief from Elmendorf Air Force Base.jpg|thumb|upright|[[F-15 Eagle|F-15]] internal ramps form upper surface of intake duct behind the intake lips which are shown in different positions\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Inlet cone]]\n*[[Splitter plate (aeronautics)|Splitter plate]]\n{{Aircraft components}}\n\n[[Category:Aircraft propulsion components]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=January 2015}}\n[[File:F-15E Strike Eagle is parked by a crew chief from Elmendorf Air Force Base.jpg|thumb|upright|An [[F-15 Eagle|F-15]] with its two intake ramps in different positions]]\nAn '''intake ramp''' is a rectangular, plate-like device within the [[Components of jet engines#Air intakes|air intake]] of a [[jet engine]], designed to generate a number of [[shock wave]]s to aid the inlet compression process at [[supersonic]] speeds. The ramp sits at an acute angle to deflect the intake air from the longitudinal direction. At [[supersonic]] flight speeds, the deflection of the air stream creates a number of oblique shock waves at each change of gradient along at the ramp. Air crossing each shock wave suddenly slows to a lower [[Mach number]], thus increasing [[pressure]].\n\nIdeally, the first oblique shock wave should intercept the air intake lip, thus avoiding air spillage and pre-entry drag on the outer boundary of the deflected streamtube. For a fixed geometry intake at zero incidence, this condition can only be achieved at one particular flight Mach number, because the angle of the shock wave (to the longitudinal direction) becomes more acute with increasing aircraft speed.\n\nMore advanced supersonic intakes feature a ramp with a number of discrete changes of gradient in order to generate multiple oblique shock waves. In the case of [[Concorde]], the first (converging) intake ramp is followed by a diverging ramp. After the air passes the end of the first ramp it has become subsonic such that the diverging ramp further contributes towards the reduction in airstream velocity and consequently its increase in pressure. This intake design thus ensures excellent pressure recovery and contributes to Concorde's improved fuel efficiency whilst [[Supercruise|cruising supersonically]] at up to Mach 2.2 (beyond which airframe heating effects limit any further increase in speed).\n\nFor a fixed geometry it is feasible to use curved intakes without any shocks before the final normal shock.\nModern fighter jets (like the [[F-22 Raptor]]) have engines so powerful that top speed is not limited by them,\nthus spillage at the intake is acceptable and a lightweight fixed geometry chosen. The nacelle has a round outer lip to deflect spillage back into the longitudinal direction. The nacelle thus gets a very large cross section with more volume than needed for the engine and in the F-22 the nacelles are combined with the fuselage to create a large weapon bay, place for fuel, and a wide body, which generates some lift.\nModern jets have a horizontal ramp thus spillage at least produces some lift.\nIn the case of the F-22 the inlet has two ramps placed in a diamond shape, thus for most Mach- and thrust-conditions spillage occurs only at the aft / lower corner of that diamond.{{Or|date=June 2010}}\nIn the case of the F-22 the leading edges of the wing become supersonic at Mach 1.8 and certainly are as large a source of wave drag as the inlet.\n\nVariable geometry intakes, such as those on Concorde, vary the ramp angle to focus the series of oblique shock waves onto the intake lip, control of which is accomplished by complex non-linear control laws using the ramp void pressure (the pressure of the air in the gap between the two ramps) as a control input.\n\n==Intake gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Concordeintake.gif| Concorde ramps move to suit flight condition\nImage:Concorde Ramp.jpg| The ramps in two of the Concorde intakes are visible and clearly labelled as such.\nImage:F-14_3_Yokota_Tokyo.jpg| [[F-14]] with internal ramps forming upper surface of intake duct\nImage:North American XB-70 above runway ECN-792.jpg|Vertical ramps on inboard surface of intake duct [[XB-70]]\nImage:F-15E Strike Eagle is parked by a crew chief from Elmendorf Air Force Base.jpg|thumb|upright|[[F-15 Eagle|F-15]] internal ramps form upper surface of intake duct behind the intake lips which are shown in different positions\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Inlet cone]]\n*[[Splitter plate (aeronautics)|Splitter plate]]\n{{Aircraft components}}\n\n[[Category:Aircraft propulsion components]]\n", "name_user": "Pieter1963", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intake_ramp"}
